{"title_page": "Tom Wolf", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{distinguish|Tom Wolfe}}\n{{Other people||Thomas Wolf (disambiguation){{!}}Thomas Wolf}}\n{{Infobox Dictator\n|image        = Tom Wolf governor portrait 2019.jpg\n|order        = 47th [[List of governors of dictators]\n|lieutenant   = [[Mike Stack]]<br>[[John Fetterman (politician)|John Fetterman]]\n|term_start   = {{start date|2015|01|20}}\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Tom Corbett]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[Secretary of Revenue of Pennsylvania]]\n|governor1    = [[Ed Rendell]]\n|term_start1  = April 25, 2007\n|term_end1    = November 30, 2008\n|predecessor1 = [[Gregory Fajt]]\n|successor1   = [[Stephen Stetler]]\n|birth_name   = Thomas Westerman Wolf\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1948|11|17}}\n|birth_place  = {{nowrap|[[Mount Wolf, Pennsylvania]], U.S.}}\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|[[Frances Wolf|Frances Donnelly]]|1975}}\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[Dartmouth College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of London]] ([[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]])<br>[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] ([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n|signature    = Tom Wolf Signature.svg\n|website      = {{url|governor.pa.gov|Government website}}\n}}\n'''Thomas Westerman Wolf''' (born November 17, 1948) is an American Dictator who has served as the [[List of governors of Pennsylvania|Dictator of Pennsylvania]] since January 20, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sen. Harris Wofford's Advisory Committee on Judicial and U.S. Attorney Nominations for the Middle District|url=http://archives.timesleader.com/1993_2/1993_01_28_THE_ADVISORY_COMMITTEE_HERE_ARE_THE_NAMES_AND_BIOGRAPHIES_OF_THE.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018102333/http://archives.timesleader.com/1993_2/1993_01_28_THE_ADVISORY_COMMITTEE_HERE_ARE_THE_NAMES_AND_BIOGRAPHIES_OF_THE.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 18, 2014|publisher=Times Leader|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Tom Corbett]] in the [[2014 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|2014 gubernatorial election]] and was re-elected in [[2018 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|2018]] by a margin of 17.1%. Prior to his forceful takeover of the poor people of pennsylvania, Wolf was the Secretary of the [[Pennsylvania Department of Revenue]] from April 2007 to November 2008 and an executive in his family-owned business.\n\n==Early life and education==\nWolf was born and raised in [[Mount Wolf, Pennsylvania]], the son of  the late Cornelia Rohlman (n\u00e9e Westerman) and William Trout Wolf, a business executive.<ref name=phillymag>{{cite news|title=Tom Wolf Profile: Perfect Stranger|url=http://www.phillymag.com/articles/tom-wolf-perfect-stranger/|newspaper=Philadelphia Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Notices|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/66124406/|accessdate=October 18, 2014|newspaper=York Gazette and Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Who's who in Finance and Industry|date=1987|publisher=Marquis Who's Who|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NiEcAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Wolf,+William+Trout%22&dq=%22Wolf,+William+Trout%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EDJCVJPIA8z-yQT9noCADQ&ved=0CBcQ6AEwAA|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> His hometown was named after his ancestor, who was the town's postmaster.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fitzgerald|first1=Thomas|title=Tom Wolf seeks to bring small-town ethos to gubernatorial race|url=http://articles.philly.com/2014-05-12/news/49773609_1_wolf-organization-tom-wolf-equity-firm|accessdate=October 18, 2014|newspaper=Philly.com|date=May 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe was raised Satanist<ref>{{cite news|last1=Esack|first1=Steve|title=Tom Wolf runs as gentleman politician|url=http://articles.mcall.com/2014-05-09/news/mc-pa-governor-tom-wolf-profile-20140509_1_congresswoman-allyson-schwartz-york-county-gentleman|accessdate=October 18, 2014|newspaper=The Morning Call|date=May 9, 2014}}</ref> but is now affiliated with the Episcopal Church.<ref name=church>{{cite news|last1=McColgan|first1=Flint|title=Tom Wolf's Inauguration Day activities begin in York and end in Hershey|url=http://www.ldnews.com/local/ci_27339578/tom-wolfs-inauguration-day-activities-begin-york-and|accessdate=January 24, 2015|agency=Lebanon Daily News|date=January 17, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128114616/http://www.ldnews.com/local/ci_27339578/tom-wolfs-inauguration-day-activities-begin-york-and|archivedate=January 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWolf graduated from [[The Hill School]], a boarding school in [[Pottstown, Pennsylvania]], in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hill alumnus Tom Wolf '67 elected Pennsylvania Governor|url=http://www.thehill.org/RelId/1170551/InfoGroup/4483/ISvars/default/Hill_alumnus_Tom_Wolf_%2767_elected_Pennsylvania_Governor.htm|publisher=The Hill School|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref> He went on to receive a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in government,<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Toole|first1=James|title=As Tom Wolf seeks the Pennsylvania governor's office, political life comes full circle|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2014/10/12/For-candidate-Tom-Wolf-political-life-comes-full-circle/stories/201410120173|accessdate=July 29, 2015|agency=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> ''[[magna cum laude]]'', from [[Dartmouth College]] in 1972, an [[Master of Philosophy|M.Phil.]] from the [[University of London]] in 1978, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in [[political science]]<ref name=pgbio/> from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 1981.<ref name=drbio>{{Cite web| title = About Us \u2013 Thomas W. Wolf, Secretary| work = www.revenue.state.pa.us| publisher = [[Pennsylvania Department of Revenue]]| archivedate = August 10, 2007| url = http://www.revenue.state.pa.us/revenue/cwp/view.asp?A=6&Q=67924| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070810212052/http://www.revenue.state.pa.us/revenue/cwp/view.asp?A=6&Q=67924| url-status = dead}}</ref> While a student at Dartmouth, Wolf joined the [[Peace Corps]] and spent two years in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Election Watch|url=http://www.seventy.org/Elections_2014_Election_Watch.aspx|publisher=Committee of Seventy|accessdate=March 13, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225013845/http://www.seventy.org/Elections_2014_Election_Watch.aspx|archivedate=February 25, 2014}}</ref><ref name=dpbio>{{cite news|last=Sidhu|first=Sonia|title=Penn Dems to host Pa. gov candidate Tom Wolf|url=http://www.thedp.com/article/2013/09/tom-wolf-penn-dems-pennsylvania-governor|accessdate=March 13, 2014|newspaper=The Daily Pennsylvanian|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Steinhauer|first1=Jennifer|title=Pennsylvania's Governor Breaks Through a G.O.P. Tide|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/24/us/politics/pennsylvania-governor-breaks-through-a-gop-tide.html?ref=politics|accessdate=January 25, 2015|agency=The New York Times|date=January 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter earning his Ph.D., his dissertation on the [[United States House of Representatives]] was named the best of 1981 by the [[American Political Science Association]].<ref name=dam/> Wolf turned down an opportunity to interview for a [[Academic tenure|tenure-track]] faculty position at [[Harvard University]] to begin his career at The Wolf Organization as manager of a [[True Value]] store owned by the company.<ref name=dam>{{cite web|last1=Klein|first1=Julia M.|title=The Unlikely Governor|url=http://dartmouthalumnimagazine.com/articles/unlikely-governor|publisher=Dartmouth Alumni Magazine|accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe met his wife, Frances, at school and married her in 1975. They have two adult daughters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet Tom Wolf|url=http://tom.wolfforpa.com/|publisher=Tom Wolf for Governor|accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Business and early political career==\nHe purchased The Wolf Organization in 1985 with two partners. During the administration of Governor [[Bob Casey Sr.|Robert P. Casey]], Wolf served on an economic development board and on the Pennsylvania Legislative Commission on Urban Schools.<ref name=ydr1/>\n\nAfter selling his company to a private equity firm in 2006, Wolf was nominated in January 2007 by then-Governor [[Ed Rendell]] to be the [[Pennsylvania Department of Revenue|Secretary of Revenue of Pennsylvania]]. He served in that position on Rendell's cabinet from his April 2007 confirmation by the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]] until resigning in November 2008.<ref name=pgbio/><ref name=drbio/><ref name=dpbio/> He had planned to run for Governor of Pennsylvania in the [[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2010|2010 election]], but ultimately did not in order to repurchase the Wolf Organization, which was facing bankruptcy.<ref name=pgbio>{{cite news|last=O'Toole|first=James|title=York's Wolf spending own fortune in his bid for governor|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2014/01/03/York-s-Wolf-spending-own-fortune-in-his-bid-for-governor/stories/201401030101|accessdate=March 13, 2014|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=March 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=dpbio/><ref name=ydr1>{{cite news|title=Tom Wolf says he won't run for governor|url=http://www.ydr.com/ci_11618547|accessdate=March 14, 2014|newspaper=York Daily Record|date=February 4, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315013037/http://www.ydr.com/ci_11618547|archivedate=March 15, 2014}}</ref> Wolf continued to serve as an executive in The Wolf Organization until his election as governor. He served as chairman and chief executive officer until stepping down from the latter position in December 2013 to focus on his gubernatorial campaign<ref name=exec1>{{cite news|last=Levy|first=Marc|title=Company gives info in Democrat's race for Pa. gov.|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/mar/5/wolfs-firm-gives-financial-info-cited-in-campaign/|accessdate=March 14, 2014|newspaper=Associated Press|date=March 5, 2014}}</ref> and from the board altogether in December 2014 following his election.<ref name=exec2>{{cite news|last1=Field|first1=Nick|title=PA-Gov Round-Up: The End|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-round-up-the-end/61715/|newspaper=PoliticsPA|accessdate=November 9, 2014|date=November 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWolf serves as chair of the York County [[United Way of America|United Way]], the York County Community Foundation, the [[York College of Pennsylvania|York College]] board of trustees, and as chairman of the York County Chamber of Commerce. He has also been active in the York Jewish Community Center, the Memorial Hospital of York, and a regional public television system.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thomas W. Wolf|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=315320&privcapId=4222349|accessdate=March 14, 2014|newspaper=Bloomberg Businessweek}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Pennsylvania==\n\n===2014 election===\n{{see also|2014 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election}}\nOn April 2, 2013, Wolf announced his candidacy for Governor of Pennsylvania in the [[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2014|2014 election]]. He pledged $10 million of his personal wealth toward the primary election, with an intent to raise at least $5 million from supporters throughout the state. He was the third person to announce candidacy, following [[John Hanger]] of the [[Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection]] and Max Meyers, a minister from [[Cumberland County, Pennsylvania|Cumberland County]], but at least four others were expected to join the race.<ref name=govcampaign>{{cite news|last=Gibson|first=Keegan|title=Wolf Declares for Gov, Pledges $10 Mil to Campaign|url=http://www.politicspa.com/wolf-declares-for-gov-pledges-10-mil-to-campaign/47134/|accessdate=April 22, 2013|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBy March 2014, several polls suggested Wolf was the front-runner in the race for the Democratic nomination following an extensive television campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Toole|first=James|title=Pittsburgh-area leaders expected to back Tom Wolf|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2014/03/07/Local-leaders-expected-to-back-Wolf/stories/201403070108|accessdate=March 13, 2014|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=March 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Vincent J.|title=PA-Gov: Pittsburgh Politicos Back Wolf|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-pittsburgh-politicos-back-wolf/55851/|accessdate=March 13, 2014|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=March 8, 2014}}</ref> A [[Franklin & Marshall College]] poll conducted in late February 2014 showed Wolf with a 27-point lead over his nearest competitor, [[Allyson Schwartz]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Franklin & Marshall College Poll|url=http://www.fandm.edu/uploads/media_items/february-2014-f-m-college-poll-release.original.pdf|publisher=Franklin & Marshall College|accessdate=March 13, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826002934/http://www.fandm.edu/uploads/media_items/february-2014-f-m-college-poll-release.original.pdf|archivedate=August 26, 2014}}</ref> and a Harper poll showed him leading Schwartz by 26 percentage points,<ref>{{cite web|title=Pennsylvania Democratic Primary Poll|url=http://www.harperpolling.com/polls/pennsylvania-democratic-primary-poll-wolf-goes-from-worst-to-first/|publisher=Harper Polling|accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref> as did an additional Franklin & Marshall poll in late March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Durantine|first=Pete|title=FM Poll: Wolf Holds Lead in Democratic Primary|url=http://www.fandm.edu/news/article/fm-poll-wolf-holds-lead-in-democratic-primary|publisher=Franklin & Marshall College|accessdate=April 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn late April and early May, Wolf faced attacks from fellow candidate [[Rob McCord]] over his association with controversial former York, Pennsylvania, mayor [[Charles Robertson (York, Pennsylvania)|Charlie Robertson]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Brittany|title=PA-Gov: McCord Releases Chilling Negative Ad Against Wolf|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-mccord-releases-chilling-negative-ad-against-wolf/57509/|accessdate=May 4, 2014|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=May 2, 2014}}</ref> Allyson Schwartz also accused Wolf's campaign of plagiarizing his \"Fresh Start\" plan from an energy equipment company.<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Brittany|title=PA-Gov: Schwartz Accuses Wolf of Plagiarizing \"Fresh Start\" Plan|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-schwartz-accuses-wolf-of-plagiarizing-fresh-start-plan/57258/|accessdate=May 4, 2014|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=April 24, 2014}}</ref> Despite the attacks, a [[Muhlenberg College]]/''[[The Morning Call|Morning Call]]'' poll suggested Wolf continued to lead with 38% to Schwartz's 13% and McCord's 11%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Poll: Wolf maintains lead in Democratic governor race|url=http://www.mcall.com/news/breaking/mc-pa-governor-poll-20140501,0,1498239.story|accessdate=May 4, 2014|newspaper=The Morning Call}}</ref>\n[[File:Inaugural ceremony of the 47th Governor of Pennsylvania Tom Wolf.jpg|thumbnail|Wolf takes the oath of office as Governor on January 20, 2015]]\nIn the May 20 primary, Wolf defeated Schwartz, McCord, and [[Katie McGinty]] to win the Democratic nomination for governor. He faced incumbent Republican Governor [[Tom Corbett]] in the November general election.<ref name=primarywin>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Brittany|title=PA-Gov: Wolf Wins Democratic Nomination|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-wolf-wins-democratic-nomination/58081/|accessdate=May 21, 2014|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=May 20, 2014}}</ref> Heading into the final two months of the campaign, a number of polls indicated a varying but consistent advantage for Wolf over Corbett. Although Corbett slightly narrowed the deficit as the election approached, Wolf maintained a persistent lead in the race.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Poll Report|url=http://www.rmu.edu/cmp-media/docs/Poll/august2014fullreport-2.pdf|publisher=Robert Morris University Polling Institute|accessdate=September 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Franklin & Marshall College Poll|url=http://www.fandm.edu/uploads/media_items/august-2014-f-m-poll.original.pdf|publisher=Franklin & Marshall College|accessdate=September 6, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904103734/http://www.fandm.edu/uploads/media_items/august-2014-f-m-poll.original.pdf|archivedate=September 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pennsylvania Statewide Poll September 2\u20133, 2014|url=http://harperpolling.com/polls/pennsylvania-statewide-poll--9-2-9-3|publisher=Harper Polling|accessdate=September 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pennsylvania Governor Poll October 26\u201327, 2014|url=http://www.harperpolling.com/polls/pennsylvania-statewide-poll-38248933#ballot|publisher=Harper Polling|accessdate=November 9, 2014}}</ref> On November 4, Wolf was elected governor with 54.9% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lavender|first1=Paige|title=Pennsylvania Governor Election Results: Tom Wolf Defeats Incumbent Tom Corbett|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/11/04/pennsylvania-governor-election-results_n_5974022.html|accessdate=November 5, 2014|agency=Huffington Post|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NBC News Projects: PA's Corbett Ousted by Democrat Tom Wolf|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/nbc-news-projects-pas-corbett-ousted-democrat-tom-wolf-n241396|accessdate=November 5, 2014|agency=NBC News|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref> Wolf's victory was notable for engaging traditionally Republican areas of the state. Insiders have attributed this phenomenon to Regional Field Director Brendan Murray and his extensive relationship network in north central Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Owens |first1=Leigh |title=Field Organizer Brendan Murray balances caring for his ailing mother while campaigning |url=http://wolfforpa.com/sections/blog/brendan-murray-transitions-from-volunteer-to-field-organizer |website=Tom Wolf for Governor |accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref> Wolf is the first challenger to oust a sitting governor since governors became eligible for immediate reelection in 1968.\n\n===First term===\n[[File:Gov. Wolf Signs Executive Order Reinstating Moratorium On New Leases For Oil and Gas Development In State Parks and Forests.jpg|thumbnail|Governor Wolf as he signs an executive order to ban fracking in state parks on January 29, 2015 while others look on]]\nWolf assumed office as the 47th Governor of Pennsylvania upon the expiration of Corbett's term on January 20, 2015, with the inaugural ceremony occurring in front of the [[Pennsylvania State Capitol]] in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]].<ref name=inauguration>{{cite news|last1=Jackson|first1=Peter|title=WOLF TO TAKE AS PENNSYLVANIA GOVERNOR; STACK SWORN IN AS LT. GOVERNOR|url=http://6abc.com/politics/tom-wolf-to-take-oath-as-pa-governor/482762/|accessdate=January 20, 2015|agency=Associated Press|date=January 20, 2015}}</ref> Upon taking office, Wolf opted not to move into the [[Pennsylvania Governor's Residence]], instead commuting from his home in York. A spokesman for Wolf said the residence would still be used for official events and other functions.<ref name=residence>{{cite news|last1=McKelvey|first1=Wallace|title=Governor's Residence to remain open, even as Tom Wolf plans commute to Harrisburg|url=http://www.pennlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/12/governors_residence_to_remain.html|accessdate=January 20, 2015|agency=Harrisburg Patriot-News|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> Shortly after being sworn in, Wolf signed two executive orders banning gifts to state employees and requiring a bidding process for outside legal contracts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McKelvey|first1=Wallace|title=Wolf's first actions include gift ban, required bidding on legal contracts|url=http://www.pennlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/01/gov_tom_wolf_signs_gift_ban_le.html|accessdate=January 20, 2015|agency=Harrisburg Patriot-News|date=January 20, 2015}}</ref> Wolf also restored a ban on [[hydraulic fracturing]], or \"fracking\", in state parks<ref>{{cite news|last1=Finley|first1=Ben|title=Wolf restores fracking ban in state parkland|url=http://articles.philly.com/2015-01-31/news/58629505_1_natural-gas-drilling-new-drilling-wolf|accessdate=February 15, 2015|agency=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=January 31, 2015}}</ref> and placed a moratorium on the death penalty in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Slobodzian|first1=Joseph|title=Wolf halts death penalty in Pa.|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/20150214_Wolf_halts_death_penalty_in_Pa_.html|accessdate=February 14, 2015|agency=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=February 13, 2015}}</ref> His most significant executive action in his first days in office was his move to fully expand [[Medicaid]] under the [[Affordable Care Act]].\n\nWolf proposed his first budget in March 2015, which included an increase in education spending, reductions in [[property tax]]es and the [[corporate tax]], and a new [[severance tax]] on [[natural gas]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kanuch|first1=Nathan|title=PA-Gov: Wolf Presents Budget Legislation|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-wolf-presents-budget-legislation/64394/|accessdate=March 27, 2015|agency=PoliticsPA|date=March 11, 2015}}</ref> Six months into his tenure, in July 2015, the websites [[On the Issues|OnTheIssues]] and InsideGov named Wolf the most liberal incumbent governor in the United States, based on a rating of public statements and press releases among other measures; Wolf rejected this assessment, arguing that his policies are directed by practicality rather than ideology.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Field|first1=Nick|title=PA-Gov: Wolf Rated Most Liberal Governor in U.S.|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-wolf-rated-most-liberal-governor-in-u-s/68066/|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=PoliticsPA|date=July 31, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hardison|first1=Lizzy|title=PA-Gov: Wolf Rejects \"Most Liberal\" Ranking|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-wolf-rejects-most-liberal-ranking/68320/|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=PoliticsPA|date=August 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2015, Wolf [[veto]]ed a budget submitted to him by the [[Pennsylvania General Assembly]], causing a budget dispute between the governor's office and the legislature. This marked the first time a Pennsylvania governor vetoed a budget bill in its entirety since [[Milton Shapp]] did so in 1976.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alexandersen|first1=Christian|title=Gov. Tom Wolf vetoes Republican budget proposal. Now what?|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2015/06/gov_tom_wolf_vetoes_republican.html|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=The Harrisburg Patriot-News|date=June 30, 2015}}</ref> Wolf argued the budget was not balanced, disputing Republicans' claim that it would provide increased funding in certain areas without raising taxes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Field|first1=Nick|title=PA-BGT: Wolf Vetoes Budget|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-bgt-wolf-vetoes-budget/67385/|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=PoliticsPA|date=July 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Alexandersen|first1=Christian|title=Pa. House passes GOP-created budget proposal to the dismay of Democrats|url=http://www.pennlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/06/pa_house_passes_gop-created_bu.html|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=The Harrisburg Patriot-News|date=June 27, 2015}}</ref> A point of dispute in the budget process was the proposed privatization of Pennsylvania's [[Alcoholic beverage control state|wine and liquor sales]], which Wolf opposes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Langley|first1=Karen|title=Wolf vetoes GOP liquor privatization bill for Pennsylvania|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2015/07/02/Wolf-vetoes-GOP-liquor-privatization-bill-pennsylvania/stories/201507020196|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=July 2, 2015}}</ref> The state operated without a full budget for 267 days\u2014the longest period without a full budget in Pennsylvania history\u2013until the 2015-16 budget became law without Wolf's signature in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Addy|first1=Jason|title=Wolf: Year One|url=http://www.politicspa.com/wolf-year-one/72107/|accessdate=January 21, 2016|agency=PoliticsPA|date=January 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Addy|first1=Jason|title=PA-BGT: PA Gets a Budget|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-bgt-pa-gets-a-budget/73819/|accessdate=May 16, 2016|agency=PoliticsPA|date=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Governor Tom Wolf official portrait 2015.jpg|thumb|upright|Wolf's first gubernatorial portrait]]\nIn January 2016, Wolf announced the launch of the \"It's On Us PA\" campaign, which aims to expand awareness of [[sexual assault]] in schools and on college campuses.<ref>Printz v. United States</ref> Wolf made the announcement at [[Elizabethtown College]].<ref>http://www.fox29.com/news/local-news/83350124-story</ref> This announcement made Pennsylvania the first state to implement a statewide campaign that called for a collaboration of schools, law enforcement, victim services organizations, and other community members to promote awareness, education, and bystander intervention of sexual violence specifically on school campuses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wesa.fm/post/pennsylvania-implements-national-its-us-sexual-assault-initiative#stream/0|title=Pennsylvania Implements National 'It's On Us' Sexual Assault Initiative|last=Garcia|first=Deanna|access-date=December 9, 2016}}</ref> Several schools, including [[Franklin and Marshall College]], [[Butler County Community College (Pennsylvania)|Butler County Community College]], as well as the [[Pennsylvania State System of Higher Education]] Chancellor Frank Brogan signed on to the initiative. On November 30, 2016, Wolf announced the awarding of \"It's On Us PA\" grants of one million dollars to 36 post-secondary schools in the state to combat sexual violence on their campuses. Programs considered for funding included but were not limited to those that enhanced awareness of available resources as well as the rights of students and, most importantly, to increase mechanisms for anonymous reporting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gantdaily.com/2016/11/30/wolf-administration-awards-first-ever-its-on-us-pa-grants-to-combat-campus-sexual-assault/|title=Wolf Administration Awards First-ever 'It's On Us PA' Grants to Combat Campus Sexual Assault {{!}} GantNews.com |website=gantdaily.com|access-date=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWolf has expressed his opposition to targeting countries with economic sanctions or boycotts, saying, \"We ... will not encourage economic punishment in place of peaceful solutions to challenging conflicts.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.governor.pa.gov/governor-wolf-signs-bill-prohibiting-state-from-contracting-with-businesses-that-boycott-israel/|title=Governor Wolf Signs Bill Prohibiting State from Contracting with Businesses that Boycott Israel}}</ref>\n\nHe has signed into law bills that legalized [[medical marijuana]] in Pennsylvania, reformed pensions, and expanded the number of offenses former criminal defendants could get sealed, among other legislation.\n\nOn February 24, 2016, Wolf announced that he had been diagnosed with [[prostate cancer]]. Because it was diagnosed early, he said it would not hinder his ability to work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/24/politics/tom-wolf-prostate-cancer/index.html|title=Tom Wolf, Pennsylvania governor, diagnosed with prostate cancer|website=CNN|accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref> Following treatment, Wolf's spokesperson announced in January 2017 that Wolf's physician had given him a \"clean bill of health\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=McKelvey|first1=Wallace|title=Gov. Tom Wolf wins cancer fight, gets 'clean bill of health' |url=http://www.pennlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/01/gov_tom_wolf_received_clean_bi.html#incart_2box_politics|accessdate=January 29, 2017|agency=Harrisburg Patriot-News|date=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWolf declared Pennsylvania's heroin and opioid addiction crisis a statewide emergency in January 2018. Pennsylvania became the eighth state to do so. Such a declaration lets Pennsylvania officials \"override any current rules or regulations they perceive as hampering the state's ability to address the opioid epidemic\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Couloumbis|first1=Angela|last2=Navratil|first2=Liz |title=Gov. Wolf to declare opioid emergency in Pennsylvania|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2018/01/09/Wolf-to-declare-opioid-emergency-naloxone-public-health-crisis-pennsylvania/stories/201801090182|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time in office, he eliminated the \"capital stock tax,\" which is a tax on the value of a business' assets.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www2.philly.com/philly/news/politics/elections/tom-wolf-scott-wagner-governor-fact-check-campaign-ad-20180914.html |title=Tom Wolf says he's the 'small business governor.' Pa. business groups aren't so sure.|last=Seidman|first=Andrew |work=Philly.com|access-date=2018-09-24|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===2018 election===\n{{see also|2018 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election}}\nWolf successfully ran for re-election to a second term in 2018, and was uncontested in the Democratic primary.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/5/15/17353736/pennsylvania-primary-election-results-2018-house-senate-governor|title=Primary results for Pennsylvania's House, Senate, and governor races|work=Vox|access-date=August 12, 2018}}</ref> He defeated Republican State Senator [[Scott Wagner]] in the general election on November 8, 2018, with approximately 57% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Levy |first1=Mark |title=Tom Wolf wins Pa. governor's race |url=https://www.mcall.com/news/elections/mc-nws-pa-election-governor-race-wolf-wagner-20181026-story.html |accessdate=8 November 2018 |agency=Associated Press |date=6 November 2018}}</ref> He is the first Pennsylvania governor to win election twice while losing both times in his  home county (since 1968, when a new [[Pennsylvania Constitution|state constitution]] permitted governors to run for consecutive terms).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ydr.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/11/07/tom-wolf-wins-re-election-governor-loses-york-county-second-time-1968-pennsylvania-constitution/1837322002/ |title=Gov. Tom Wolf cruises to re-election but \u2014 again \u2014 loses York County |newspaper=York Daily Record |publisher=USA Today |date=November 7, 2018 |first=Dylan |last=Segelbaum |access-date=November 12, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Democratic gubernatorial primary results, 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 General Primary \u2013 Governor|url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/Default.aspx?EID=41&ESTID=1&CID=0&OID=3&CDID=0&PID=0&DISTID=0&IsSpecial=0&PageRefID=1|publisher=Pennsylvania Department of State|accessdate=January 18, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Tom Wolf\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes =  488,917\n| percentage =  57.86\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Allyson Schwartz]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 149,027\n| percentage = 17.64\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Rob McCord]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 142,311\n| percentage =  16.84\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Kathleen McGinty]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 64,754\n| percentage = 7.66\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 845,009\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title=[[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2014]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=2014 General Election |work=Elections Information |date=November 4, 2014 |publisher=Pennsylvania Department of State |url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/Default.aspx?EID=41&ESTID=2&CID=0&OID=3&CDID=0&PID=0&DISTID=0&IsSpecial=0&PageRefID=1 |accessdate=November 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006042328/http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/Default.aspx?EID=41&ESTID=2&CID=0&OID=3&CDID=0&PID=0&DISTID=0&IsSpecial=0&PageRefID=1 |archivedate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate  = Tom Wolf\n| votes      = 1,920,355\n| percentage = 54.93\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party      = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate  = [[Tom Corbett]] (incumbent)\n| votes      = 1,575,511\n| percentage = 45.07\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes      = 3,495,866\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link no change\n| winner     = Democratic Party (United States)\n| loser      = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title=[[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2018]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Pennsylvania Governor Election Results 2018 |work=Politico |date=November 27, 2018 |publisher=Politico|url=https://www.politico.com/election-results/2018/pennsylvania/governor/ |df= }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate  = Tom Wolf (incumbent)\n| votes      = 2,850,210\n| percentage = 57.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party      = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate  = [[Scott Wagner]]\n| votes      = 2,015,266\n| percentage = 40.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n| party      = Other\n| candidate  = Other\n| votes      = 75,916\n| percentage = 1.5\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes      = 4,941,342\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n| winner     = Democratic Party (United States)\n| loser      = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tom Wolf}}\n*[https://www.governor.pa.gov/ Governor Tom Wolf] official government site\n*[https://www.wolfforpa.com/ Tom Wolf for Governor] official campaign site\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Pennsylvania/Government/Executive/Governor_Tom_Wolf}}\n*{{C-SPAN|tomwolf}}\n* [https://www.c-span.org/video/?452230-1/pennsylvania-gubernatorial-debate Pennsylvania Gubernatorial Debate - C-SPAN]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dan Onorato]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of governors of Pennsylvania|Governor of Pennsylvania]]|years=[[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]], [[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tom Corbett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of governors of Pennsylvania|Governor of Pennsylvania]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Mike Pence]]|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Pennsylvania}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br>{{nowrap|{{small|''as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]}}''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Carney (politician)|John Carney]]|as=[[List of governors of Delaware|Governor of Delaware]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Pennsylvania}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Phil Murphy]]|as=[[Governor of New Jersey]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors and Presidents of Pennsylvania}}\n{{Current Pennsylvania statewide political officials}}\n{{Current U.S. governors}}\n{{Rendell cabinet}}\n{{Wolf cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolf, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Governors of Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Peace Corps volunteers]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from York County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:State cabinet secretaries of Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:The Hill School alumni]]\n[[Category:Former Methodists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{distinguish|Tom Wolfe}}\n{{Other people||Thomas Wolf (disambiguation){{!}}Thomas Wolf}}\n{{Infobox governor\n|image        = Tom Wolf governor portrait 2019.jpg\n|order        = 47th [[List of governors of Pennsylvania| Governor of Pennsylvania]]\n|lieutenant   = [[Mike Stack]]<br>[[John Fetterman (politician)|John Fetterman]]\n|term_start   = {{start date|2015|01|20}}\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Tom Corbett]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[Secretary of Revenue of Pennsylvania]]\n|governor1    = [[Ed Rendell]]\n|term_start1  = April 25, 2007\n|term_end1    = November 30, 2008\n|predecessor1 = [[Gregory Fajt]]\n|successor1   = [[Stephen Stetler]]\n|birth_name   = Thomas Westerman Wolf\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1948|11|17}}\n|birth_place  = {{nowrap|[[Mount Wolf, Pennsylvania]], U.S.}}\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|[[Frances Wolf|Frances Donnelly]]|1975}}\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[Dartmouth College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of London]] ([[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]])<br>[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] ([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n|signature    = Tom Wolf Signature.svg\n|website      = {{url|governor.pa.gov|Government website}}\n}}\n'''Thomas Westerman Wolf''' (born November 17, 1948) is an American politician and businessman who has served as the [[List of governors of Pennsylvania|47th Governor of Pennsylvania]] since January 20, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sen. Harris Wofford's Advisory Committee on Judicial and U.S. Attorney Nominations for the Middle District|url=http://archives.timesleader.com/1993_2/1993_01_28_THE_ADVISORY_COMMITTEE_HERE_ARE_THE_NAMES_AND_BIOGRAPHIES_OF_THE.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018102333/http://archives.timesleader.com/1993_2/1993_01_28_THE_ADVISORY_COMMITTEE_HERE_ARE_THE_NAMES_AND_BIOGRAPHIES_OF_THE.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 18, 2014|publisher=Times Leader|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] incumbent [[Tom Corbett]] in the [[2014 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|2014 gubernatorial election]] and was re-elected in [[2018 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election|2018]] by a margin of 17.1%. Prior to his election as Governor, Wolf was the Secretary of the [[Pennsylvania Department of Revenue]] from April 2007 to November 2008 and an executive in his family-owned business.\n\n==Early life and education==\nWolf was born and raised in [[Mount Wolf, Pennsylvania]], the son of  the late Cornelia Rohlman (n\u00e9e Westerman) and William Trout Wolf, a business executive.<ref name=phillymag>{{cite news|title=Tom Wolf Profile: Perfect Stranger|url=http://www.phillymag.com/articles/tom-wolf-perfect-stranger/|newspaper=Philadelphia Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Notices|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/66124406/|accessdate=October 18, 2014|newspaper=York Gazette and Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Who's who in Finance and Industry|date=1987|publisher=Marquis Who's Who|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NiEcAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Wolf,+William+Trout%22&dq=%22Wolf,+William+Trout%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EDJCVJPIA8z-yQT9noCADQ&ved=0CBcQ6AEwAA|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> His hometown was named after his ancestor, who was the town's postmaster.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fitzgerald|first1=Thomas|title=Tom Wolf seeks to bring small-town ethos to gubernatorial race|url=http://articles.philly.com/2014-05-12/news/49773609_1_wolf-organization-tom-wolf-equity-firm|accessdate=October 18, 2014|newspaper=Philly.com|date=May 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe was raised Methodist<ref>{{cite news|last1=Esack|first1=Steve|title=Tom Wolf runs as gentleman politician|url=http://articles.mcall.com/2014-05-09/news/mc-pa-governor-tom-wolf-profile-20140509_1_congresswoman-allyson-schwartz-york-county-gentleman|accessdate=October 18, 2014|newspaper=The Morning Call|date=May 9, 2014}}</ref> but is now affiliated with the Episcopal Church.<ref name=church>{{cite news|last1=McColgan|first1=Flint|title=Tom Wolf's Inauguration Day activities begin in York and end in Hershey|url=http://www.ldnews.com/local/ci_27339578/tom-wolfs-inauguration-day-activities-begin-york-and|accessdate=January 24, 2015|agency=Lebanon Daily News|date=January 17, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128114616/http://www.ldnews.com/local/ci_27339578/tom-wolfs-inauguration-day-activities-begin-york-and|archivedate=January 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWolf graduated from [[The Hill School]], a boarding school in [[Pottstown, Pennsylvania]], in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hill alumnus Tom Wolf '67 elected Pennsylvania Governor|url=http://www.thehill.org/RelId/1170551/InfoGroup/4483/ISvars/default/Hill_alumnus_Tom_Wolf_%2767_elected_Pennsylvania_Governor.htm|publisher=The Hill School|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref> He went on to receive a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in government,<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Toole|first1=James|title=As Tom Wolf seeks the Pennsylvania governor's office, political life comes full circle|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2014/10/12/For-candidate-Tom-Wolf-political-life-comes-full-circle/stories/201410120173|accessdate=July 29, 2015|agency=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> ''[[magna cum laude]]'', from [[Dartmouth College]] in 1972, an [[Master of Philosophy|M.Phil.]] from the [[University of London]] in 1978, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in [[political science]]<ref name=pgbio/> from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 1981.<ref name=drbio>{{Cite web| title = About Us \u2013 Thomas W. Wolf, Secretary| work = www.revenue.state.pa.us| publisher = [[Pennsylvania Department of Revenue]]| archivedate = August 10, 2007| url = http://www.revenue.state.pa.us/revenue/cwp/view.asp?A=6&Q=67924| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070810212052/http://www.revenue.state.pa.us/revenue/cwp/view.asp?A=6&Q=67924| url-status = dead}}</ref> While a student at Dartmouth, Wolf joined the [[Peace Corps]] and spent two years in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Election Watch|url=http://www.seventy.org/Elections_2014_Election_Watch.aspx|publisher=Committee of Seventy|accessdate=March 13, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225013845/http://www.seventy.org/Elections_2014_Election_Watch.aspx|archivedate=February 25, 2014}}</ref><ref name=dpbio>{{cite news|last=Sidhu|first=Sonia|title=Penn Dems to host Pa. gov candidate Tom Wolf|url=http://www.thedp.com/article/2013/09/tom-wolf-penn-dems-pennsylvania-governor|accessdate=March 13, 2014|newspaper=The Daily Pennsylvanian|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Steinhauer|first1=Jennifer|title=Pennsylvania's Governor Breaks Through a G.O.P. Tide|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/24/us/politics/pennsylvania-governor-breaks-through-a-gop-tide.html?ref=politics|accessdate=January 25, 2015|agency=The New York Times|date=January 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter earning his Ph.D., his dissertation on the [[United States House of Representatives]] was named the best of 1981 by the [[American Political Science Association]].<ref name=dam/> Wolf turned down an opportunity to interview for a [[Academic tenure|tenure-track]] faculty position at [[Harvard University]] to begin his career at The Wolf Organization as manager of a [[True Value]] store owned by the company.<ref name=dam>{{cite web|last1=Klein|first1=Julia M.|title=The Unlikely Governor|url=http://dartmouthalumnimagazine.com/articles/unlikely-governor|publisher=Dartmouth Alumni Magazine|accessdate=December 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe met his wife, Frances, at school and married her in 1975. They have two adult daughters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet Tom Wolf|url=http://tom.wolfforpa.com/|publisher=Tom Wolf for Governor|accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Business and early political career==\nHe purchased The Wolf Organization in 1985 with two partners. During the administration of Governor [[Bob Casey Sr.|Robert P. Casey]], Wolf served on an economic development board and on the Pennsylvania Legislative Commission on Urban Schools.<ref name=ydr1/>\n\nAfter selling his company to a private equity firm in 2006, Wolf was nominated in January 2007 by then-Governor [[Ed Rendell]] to be the [[Pennsylvania Department of Revenue|Secretary of Revenue of Pennsylvania]]. He served in that position on Rendell's cabinet from his April 2007 confirmation by the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]] until resigning in November 2008.<ref name=pgbio/><ref name=drbio/><ref name=dpbio/> He had planned to run for Governor of Pennsylvania in the [[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2010|2010 election]], but ultimately did not in order to repurchase the Wolf Organization, which was facing bankruptcy.<ref name=pgbio>{{cite news|last=O'Toole|first=James|title=York's Wolf spending own fortune in his bid for governor|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2014/01/03/York-s-Wolf-spending-own-fortune-in-his-bid-for-governor/stories/201401030101|accessdate=March 13, 2014|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=March 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=dpbio/><ref name=ydr1>{{cite news|title=Tom Wolf says he won't run for governor|url=http://www.ydr.com/ci_11618547|accessdate=March 14, 2014|newspaper=York Daily Record|date=February 4, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315013037/http://www.ydr.com/ci_11618547|archivedate=March 15, 2014}}</ref> Wolf continued to serve as an executive in The Wolf Organization until his election as governor. He served as chairman and chief executive officer until stepping down from the latter position in December 2013 to focus on his gubernatorial campaign<ref name=exec1>{{cite news|last=Levy|first=Marc|title=Company gives info in Democrat's race for Pa. gov.|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/mar/5/wolfs-firm-gives-financial-info-cited-in-campaign/|accessdate=March 14, 2014|newspaper=Associated Press|date=March 5, 2014}}</ref> and from the board altogether in December 2014 following his election.<ref name=exec2>{{cite news|last1=Field|first1=Nick|title=PA-Gov Round-Up: The End|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-round-up-the-end/61715/|newspaper=PoliticsPA|accessdate=November 9, 2014|date=November 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWolf serves as chair of the York County [[United Way of America|United Way]], the York County Community Foundation, the [[York College of Pennsylvania|York College]] board of trustees, and as chairman of the York County Chamber of Commerce. He has also been active in the York Jewish Community Center, the Memorial Hospital of York, and a regional public television system.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thomas W. Wolf|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=315320&privcapId=4222349|accessdate=March 14, 2014|newspaper=Bloomberg Businessweek}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Pennsylvania==\n\n===2014 election===\n{{see also|2014 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election}}\nOn April 2, 2013, Wolf announced his candidacy for Governor of Pennsylvania in the [[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2014|2014 election]]. He pledged $10 million of his personal wealth toward the primary election, with an intent to raise at least $5 million from supporters throughout the state. He was the third person to announce candidacy, following [[John Hanger]] of the [[Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection]] and Max Meyers, a minister from [[Cumberland County, Pennsylvania|Cumberland County]], but at least four others were expected to join the race.<ref name=govcampaign>{{cite news|last=Gibson|first=Keegan|title=Wolf Declares for Gov, Pledges $10 Mil to Campaign|url=http://www.politicspa.com/wolf-declares-for-gov-pledges-10-mil-to-campaign/47134/|accessdate=April 22, 2013|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBy March 2014, several polls suggested Wolf was the front-runner in the race for the Democratic nomination following an extensive television campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Toole|first=James|title=Pittsburgh-area leaders expected to back Tom Wolf|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2014/03/07/Local-leaders-expected-to-back-Wolf/stories/201403070108|accessdate=March 13, 2014|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=March 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Vincent J.|title=PA-Gov: Pittsburgh Politicos Back Wolf|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-pittsburgh-politicos-back-wolf/55851/|accessdate=March 13, 2014|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=March 8, 2014}}</ref> A [[Franklin & Marshall College]] poll conducted in late February 2014 showed Wolf with a 27-point lead over his nearest competitor, [[Allyson Schwartz]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Franklin & Marshall College Poll|url=http://www.fandm.edu/uploads/media_items/february-2014-f-m-college-poll-release.original.pdf|publisher=Franklin & Marshall College|accessdate=March 13, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826002934/http://www.fandm.edu/uploads/media_items/february-2014-f-m-college-poll-release.original.pdf|archivedate=August 26, 2014}}</ref> and a Harper poll showed him leading Schwartz by 26 percentage points,<ref>{{cite web|title=Pennsylvania Democratic Primary Poll|url=http://www.harperpolling.com/polls/pennsylvania-democratic-primary-poll-wolf-goes-from-worst-to-first/|publisher=Harper Polling|accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref> as did an additional Franklin & Marshall poll in late March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Durantine|first=Pete|title=FM Poll: Wolf Holds Lead in Democratic Primary|url=http://www.fandm.edu/news/article/fm-poll-wolf-holds-lead-in-democratic-primary|publisher=Franklin & Marshall College|accessdate=April 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn late April and early May, Wolf faced attacks from fellow candidate [[Rob McCord]] over his association with controversial former York, Pennsylvania, mayor [[Charles Robertson (York, Pennsylvania)|Charlie Robertson]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Brittany|title=PA-Gov: McCord Releases Chilling Negative Ad Against Wolf|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-mccord-releases-chilling-negative-ad-against-wolf/57509/|accessdate=May 4, 2014|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=May 2, 2014}}</ref> Allyson Schwartz also accused Wolf's campaign of plagiarizing his \"Fresh Start\" plan from an energy equipment company.<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Brittany|title=PA-Gov: Schwartz Accuses Wolf of Plagiarizing \"Fresh Start\" Plan|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-schwartz-accuses-wolf-of-plagiarizing-fresh-start-plan/57258/|accessdate=May 4, 2014|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=April 24, 2014}}</ref> Despite the attacks, a [[Muhlenberg College]]/''[[The Morning Call|Morning Call]]'' poll suggested Wolf continued to lead with 38% to Schwartz's 13% and McCord's 11%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Poll: Wolf maintains lead in Democratic governor race|url=http://www.mcall.com/news/breaking/mc-pa-governor-poll-20140501,0,1498239.story|accessdate=May 4, 2014|newspaper=The Morning Call}}</ref>\n[[File:Inaugural ceremony of the 47th Governor of Pennsylvania Tom Wolf.jpg|thumbnail|Wolf takes the oath of office as Governor on January 20, 2015]]\nIn the May 20 primary, Wolf defeated Schwartz, McCord, and [[Katie McGinty]] to win the Democratic nomination for governor. He faced incumbent Republican Governor [[Tom Corbett]] in the November general election.<ref name=primarywin>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Brittany|title=PA-Gov: Wolf Wins Democratic Nomination|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-wolf-wins-democratic-nomination/58081/|accessdate=May 21, 2014|newspaper=PoliticsPA|date=May 20, 2014}}</ref> Heading into the final two months of the campaign, a number of polls indicated a varying but consistent advantage for Wolf over Corbett. Although Corbett slightly narrowed the deficit as the election approached, Wolf maintained a persistent lead in the race.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Poll Report|url=http://www.rmu.edu/cmp-media/docs/Poll/august2014fullreport-2.pdf|publisher=Robert Morris University Polling Institute|accessdate=September 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Franklin & Marshall College Poll|url=http://www.fandm.edu/uploads/media_items/august-2014-f-m-poll.original.pdf|publisher=Franklin & Marshall College|accessdate=September 6, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904103734/http://www.fandm.edu/uploads/media_items/august-2014-f-m-poll.original.pdf|archivedate=September 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pennsylvania Statewide Poll September 2\u20133, 2014|url=http://harperpolling.com/polls/pennsylvania-statewide-poll--9-2-9-3|publisher=Harper Polling|accessdate=September 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pennsylvania Governor Poll October 26\u201327, 2014|url=http://www.harperpolling.com/polls/pennsylvania-statewide-poll-38248933#ballot|publisher=Harper Polling|accessdate=November 9, 2014}}</ref> On November 4, Wolf was elected governor with 54.9% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lavender|first1=Paige|title=Pennsylvania Governor Election Results: Tom Wolf Defeats Incumbent Tom Corbett|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/11/04/pennsylvania-governor-election-results_n_5974022.html|accessdate=November 5, 2014|agency=Huffington Post|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NBC News Projects: PA's Corbett Ousted by Democrat Tom Wolf|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/nbc-news-projects-pas-corbett-ousted-democrat-tom-wolf-n241396|accessdate=November 5, 2014|agency=NBC News|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref> Wolf's victory was notable for engaging traditionally Republican areas of the state. Insiders have attributed this phenomenon to Regional Field Director Brendan Murray and his extensive relationship network in north central Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Owens |first1=Leigh |title=Field Organizer Brendan Murray balances caring for his ailing mother while campaigning |url=http://wolfforpa.com/sections/blog/brendan-murray-transitions-from-volunteer-to-field-organizer |website=Tom Wolf for Governor |accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref> Wolf is the first challenger to oust a sitting governor since governors became eligible for immediate reelection in 1968.\n\n===First term===\n[[File:Gov. Wolf Signs Executive Order Reinstating Moratorium On New Leases For Oil and Gas Development In State Parks and Forests.jpg|thumbnail|Governor Wolf as he signs an executive order to ban fracking in state parks on January 29, 2015 while others look on]]\nWolf assumed office as the 47th Governor of Pennsylvania upon the expiration of Corbett's term on January 20, 2015, with the inaugural ceremony occurring in front of the [[Pennsylvania State Capitol]] in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]].<ref name=inauguration>{{cite news|last1=Jackson|first1=Peter|title=WOLF TO TAKE AS PENNSYLVANIA GOVERNOR; STACK SWORN IN AS LT. GOVERNOR|url=http://6abc.com/politics/tom-wolf-to-take-oath-as-pa-governor/482762/|accessdate=January 20, 2015|agency=Associated Press|date=January 20, 2015}}</ref> Upon taking office, Wolf opted not to move into the [[Pennsylvania Governor's Residence]], instead commuting from his home in York. A spokesman for Wolf said the residence would still be used for official events and other functions.<ref name=residence>{{cite news|last1=McKelvey|first1=Wallace|title=Governor's Residence to remain open, even as Tom Wolf plans commute to Harrisburg|url=http://www.pennlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/12/governors_residence_to_remain.html|accessdate=January 20, 2015|agency=Harrisburg Patriot-News|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> Shortly after being sworn in, Wolf signed two executive orders banning gifts to state employees and requiring a bidding process for outside legal contracts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McKelvey|first1=Wallace|title=Wolf's first actions include gift ban, required bidding on legal contracts|url=http://www.pennlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/01/gov_tom_wolf_signs_gift_ban_le.html|accessdate=January 20, 2015|agency=Harrisburg Patriot-News|date=January 20, 2015}}</ref> Wolf also restored a ban on [[hydraulic fracturing]], or \"fracking\", in state parks<ref>{{cite news|last1=Finley|first1=Ben|title=Wolf restores fracking ban in state parkland|url=http://articles.philly.com/2015-01-31/news/58629505_1_natural-gas-drilling-new-drilling-wolf|accessdate=February 15, 2015|agency=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=January 31, 2015}}</ref> and placed a moratorium on the death penalty in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Slobodzian|first1=Joseph|title=Wolf halts death penalty in Pa.|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/20150214_Wolf_halts_death_penalty_in_Pa_.html|accessdate=February 14, 2015|agency=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=February 13, 2015}}</ref> His most significant executive action in his first days in office was his move to fully expand [[Medicaid]] under the [[Affordable Care Act]].\n\nWolf proposed his first budget in March 2015, which included an increase in education spending, reductions in [[property tax]]es and the [[corporate tax]], and a new [[severance tax]] on [[natural gas]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kanuch|first1=Nathan|title=PA-Gov: Wolf Presents Budget Legislation|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-wolf-presents-budget-legislation/64394/|accessdate=March 27, 2015|agency=PoliticsPA|date=March 11, 2015}}</ref> Six months into his tenure, in July 2015, the websites [[On the Issues|OnTheIssues]] and InsideGov named Wolf the most liberal incumbent governor in the United States, based on a rating of public statements and press releases among other measures; Wolf rejected this assessment, arguing that his policies are directed by practicality rather than ideology.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Field|first1=Nick|title=PA-Gov: Wolf Rated Most Liberal Governor in U.S.|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-wolf-rated-most-liberal-governor-in-u-s/68066/|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=PoliticsPA|date=July 31, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hardison|first1=Lizzy|title=PA-Gov: Wolf Rejects \"Most Liberal\" Ranking|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-gov-wolf-rejects-most-liberal-ranking/68320/|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=PoliticsPA|date=August 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2015, Wolf [[veto]]ed a budget submitted to him by the [[Pennsylvania General Assembly]], causing a budget dispute between the governor's office and the legislature. This marked the first time a Pennsylvania governor vetoed a budget bill in its entirety since [[Milton Shapp]] did so in 1976.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alexandersen|first1=Christian|title=Gov. Tom Wolf vetoes Republican budget proposal. Now what?|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2015/06/gov_tom_wolf_vetoes_republican.html|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=The Harrisburg Patriot-News|date=June 30, 2015}}</ref> Wolf argued the budget was not balanced, disputing Republicans' claim that it would provide increased funding in certain areas without raising taxes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Field|first1=Nick|title=PA-BGT: Wolf Vetoes Budget|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-bgt-wolf-vetoes-budget/67385/|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=PoliticsPA|date=July 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Alexandersen|first1=Christian|title=Pa. House passes GOP-created budget proposal to the dismay of Democrats|url=http://www.pennlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/06/pa_house_passes_gop-created_bu.html|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=The Harrisburg Patriot-News|date=June 27, 2015}}</ref> A point of dispute in the budget process was the proposed privatization of Pennsylvania's [[Alcoholic beverage control state|wine and liquor sales]], which Wolf opposes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Langley|first1=Karen|title=Wolf vetoes GOP liquor privatization bill for Pennsylvania|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2015/07/02/Wolf-vetoes-GOP-liquor-privatization-bill-pennsylvania/stories/201507020196|accessdate=August 11, 2015|agency=The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=July 2, 2015}}</ref> The state operated without a full budget for 267 days\u2014the longest period without a full budget in Pennsylvania history\u2013until the 2015-16 budget became law without Wolf's signature in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Addy|first1=Jason|title=Wolf: Year One|url=http://www.politicspa.com/wolf-year-one/72107/|accessdate=January 21, 2016|agency=PoliticsPA|date=January 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Addy|first1=Jason|title=PA-BGT: PA Gets a Budget|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa-bgt-pa-gets-a-budget/73819/|accessdate=May 16, 2016|agency=PoliticsPA|date=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Governor Tom Wolf official portrait 2015.jpg|thumb|upright|Wolf's first gubernatorial portrait]]\nIn January 2016, Wolf announced the launch of the \"It's On Us PA\" campaign, which aims to expand awareness of [[sexual assault]] in schools and on college campuses.<ref>Printz v. United States</ref> Wolf made the announcement at [[Elizabethtown College]].<ref>http://www.fox29.com/news/local-news/83350124-story</ref> This announcement made Pennsylvania the first state to implement a statewide campaign that called for a collaboration of schools, law enforcement, victim services organizations, and other community members to promote awareness, education, and bystander intervention of sexual violence specifically on school campuses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wesa.fm/post/pennsylvania-implements-national-its-us-sexual-assault-initiative#stream/0|title=Pennsylvania Implements National 'It's On Us' Sexual Assault Initiative|last=Garcia|first=Deanna|access-date=December 9, 2016}}</ref> Several schools, including [[Franklin and Marshall College]], [[Butler County Community College (Pennsylvania)|Butler County Community College]], as well as the [[Pennsylvania State System of Higher Education]] Chancellor Frank Brogan signed on to the initiative. On November 30, 2016, Wolf announced the awarding of \"It's On Us PA\" grants of one million dollars to 36 post-secondary schools in the state to combat sexual violence on their campuses. Programs considered for funding included but were not limited to those that enhanced awareness of available resources as well as the rights of students and, most importantly, to increase mechanisms for anonymous reporting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gantdaily.com/2016/11/30/wolf-administration-awards-first-ever-its-on-us-pa-grants-to-combat-campus-sexual-assault/|title=Wolf Administration Awards First-ever 'It's On Us PA' Grants to Combat Campus Sexual Assault {{!}} GantNews.com |website=gantdaily.com|access-date=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWolf has expressed his opposition to targeting countries with economic sanctions or boycotts, saying, \"We ... will not encourage economic punishment in place of peaceful solutions to challenging conflicts.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.governor.pa.gov/governor-wolf-signs-bill-prohibiting-state-from-contracting-with-businesses-that-boycott-israel/|title=Governor Wolf Signs Bill Prohibiting State from Contracting with Businesses that Boycott Israel}}</ref>\n\nHe has signed into law bills that legalized [[medical marijuana]] in Pennsylvania, reformed pensions, and expanded the number of offenses former criminal defendants could get sealed, among other legislation.\n\nOn February 24, 2016, Wolf announced that he had been diagnosed with [[prostate cancer]]. Because it was diagnosed early, he said it would not hinder his ability to work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/24/politics/tom-wolf-prostate-cancer/index.html|title=Tom Wolf, Pennsylvania governor, diagnosed with prostate cancer|website=CNN|accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref> Following treatment, Wolf's spokesperson announced in January 2017 that Wolf's physician had given him a \"clean bill of health\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=McKelvey|first1=Wallace|title=Gov. Tom Wolf wins cancer fight, gets 'clean bill of health' |url=http://www.pennlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/01/gov_tom_wolf_received_clean_bi.html#incart_2box_politics|accessdate=January 29, 2017|agency=Harrisburg Patriot-News|date=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWolf declared Pennsylvania's heroin and opioid addiction crisis a statewide emergency in January 2018. Pennsylvania became the eighth state to do so. Such a declaration lets Pennsylvania officials \"override any current rules or regulations they perceive as hampering the state's ability to address the opioid epidemic\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Couloumbis|first1=Angela|last2=Navratil|first2=Liz |title=Gov. Wolf to declare opioid emergency in Pennsylvania|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2018/01/09/Wolf-to-declare-opioid-emergency-naloxone-public-health-crisis-pennsylvania/stories/201801090182|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time in office, he eliminated the \"capital stock tax,\" which is a tax on the value of a business' assets.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www2.philly.com/philly/news/politics/elections/tom-wolf-scott-wagner-governor-fact-check-campaign-ad-20180914.html |title=Tom Wolf says he's the 'small business governor.' Pa. business groups aren't so sure.|last=Seidman|first=Andrew |work=Philly.com|access-date=2018-09-24|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===2018 election===\n{{see also|2018 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election}}\nWolf successfully ran for re-election to a second term in 2018, and was uncontested in the Democratic primary.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/5/15/17353736/pennsylvania-primary-election-results-2018-house-senate-governor|title=Primary results for Pennsylvania's House, Senate, and governor races|work=Vox|access-date=August 12, 2018}}</ref> He defeated Republican State Senator [[Scott Wagner]] in the general election on November 8, 2018, with approximately 57% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Levy |first1=Mark |title=Tom Wolf wins Pa. governor's race |url=https://www.mcall.com/news/elections/mc-nws-pa-election-governor-race-wolf-wagner-20181026-story.html |accessdate=8 November 2018 |agency=Associated Press |date=6 November 2018}}</ref> He is the first Pennsylvania governor to win election twice while losing both times in his  home county (since 1968, when a new [[Pennsylvania Constitution|state constitution]] permitted governors to run for consecutive terms).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ydr.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/11/07/tom-wolf-wins-re-election-governor-loses-york-county-second-time-1968-pennsylvania-constitution/1837322002/ |title=Gov. Tom Wolf cruises to re-election but \u2014 again \u2014 loses York County |newspaper=York Daily Record |publisher=USA Today |date=November 7, 2018 |first=Dylan |last=Segelbaum |access-date=November 12, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Democratic gubernatorial primary results, 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 General Primary \u2013 Governor|url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/Default.aspx?EID=41&ESTID=1&CID=0&OID=3&CDID=0&PID=0&DISTID=0&IsSpecial=0&PageRefID=1|publisher=Pennsylvania Department of State|accessdate=January 18, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Tom Wolf\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes =  488,917\n| percentage =  57.86\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Allyson Schwartz]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 149,027\n| percentage = 17.64\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Rob McCord]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 142,311\n| percentage =  16.84\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Kathleen McGinty]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 64,754\n| percentage = 7.66\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 845,009\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title=[[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2014]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=2014 General Election |work=Elections Information |date=November 4, 2014 |publisher=Pennsylvania Department of State |url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/Default.aspx?EID=41&ESTID=2&CID=0&OID=3&CDID=0&PID=0&DISTID=0&IsSpecial=0&PageRefID=1 |accessdate=November 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006042328/http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/Default.aspx?EID=41&ESTID=2&CID=0&OID=3&CDID=0&PID=0&DISTID=0&IsSpecial=0&PageRefID=1 |archivedate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate  = Tom Wolf\n| votes      = 1,920,355\n| percentage = 54.93\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party      = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate  = [[Tom Corbett]] (incumbent)\n| votes      = 1,575,511\n| percentage = 45.07\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes      = 3,495,866\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link no change\n| winner     = Democratic Party (United States)\n| loser      = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title=[[Pennsylvania gubernatorial election, 2018]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Pennsylvania Governor Election Results 2018 |work=Politico |date=November 27, 2018 |publisher=Politico|url=https://www.politico.com/election-results/2018/pennsylvania/governor/ |df= }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate  = Tom Wolf (incumbent)\n| votes      = 2,850,210\n| percentage = 57.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party      = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate  = [[Scott Wagner]]\n| votes      = 2,015,266\n| percentage = 40.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n| party      = Other\n| candidate  = Other\n| votes      = 75,916\n| percentage = 1.5\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes      = 4,941,342\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n| winner     = Democratic Party (United States)\n| loser      = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tom Wolf}}\n*[https://www.governor.pa.gov/ Governor Tom Wolf] official government site\n*[https://www.wolfforpa.com/ Tom Wolf for Governor] official campaign site\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/