n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Tamil Nadu}}\n*[https://nhmtn.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/095ad0a1c0254b058fa36b32d1ab1977 COVID-19 dashboard]\n*[https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/ StopCoronaTN] \u2013 [[Department of Health and Family Welfare (Tamil Nadu)|Department of Health and Family Welfare, Tamil Nadu]] \n*[https://www.mohfw.gov.in/ Minister of Health and Family Welfare] \u2013 [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]]'s homepage\n*{{YouTube|channel=UCey5XaVBUChYMfsBcpcxeuw}} \u2013 National Health Mission Tamil Nadu channel\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n{{Portal bar|India|Medicine|Viruses|COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India by state or union territory|Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2020s in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Health in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Tamil Nadu]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Tamil Nadu, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu\n| image           = \n| width           = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = India Tamil Nadu COVID-19 map.svg\n| legend1         = Map of districts with confirmed cases (as of 20 April)\n{{legend|#a50f15|100+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#de2d26|50\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fc9272|10\u201349 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fee5d9|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = [[Chennai]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n<!-- The confirmed, active, recovery and deaths cases are fetched from the Wikidata; Kindly don't delete the codes below.-->| confirmed_cases = {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1603|qual=P585|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}\n| active_cases    = {{formatnum: {{#expr: {{formatnum: {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1603|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}-{{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P8010|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}-{{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1120|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}} -3 |R}} }} }}{{refn|group=note|2 deaths cross notified to other states. 1 patient died after turning negative for infection.}}\n| recovery_cases  = {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P8010|qual=P585|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}\n| deaths          = {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1120|qual=P585|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}\n| suspected_cases = \n| territories     = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#Cases by districts|36 districts]]\n| total_ili       = 5<ref name=\"SARI-10Apr\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=10 April 2020|title=Severe acute respiratory illness surveillance for coronavirus disease 2019, India, 2020|url=http://www.ijmr.org.in/temp/IndianJMedRes000-2175279_060232.pdf|journal=Indian Journal of Medical Research|volume=|page=5|via=}}</ref>\n| website         = {{url|https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/}}<br/>[https://nhmtn.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/095ad0a1c0254b058fa36b32d1ab1977 COVID-19 Public dashboard]\n| youtube         = \n}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in the Indian state of [[Tamil Nadu]] was reported on 7 March 2020. The [[Department of Health and Family Welfare (Tamil Nadu)|Department of Health and Family Welfare]] has confirmed a total of 1,683 cases, including 20 deaths and 752 recoveries, as of 23 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nhmtn.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/095ad0a1c0254b058fa36b32d1ab1977|title=ArcGIS Dashboards|website=nhmtn.maps.arcgis.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> As of 20 April 2020, 1302 out of 1,520 ({{Percentage|1302|1520}}) cases were from one cluster linked to a [[Tablighi Jamaat]] religious congregation [[2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|event]] that took place in [[Delhi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hpq8kc7mWg0|title=Polimer News - \u0b9f\u0bc6\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bbf \u0bb0\u0bbf\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd, \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bc8\u0baf 1,302 \u0baa\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe..!|date=2020-04-20|website=Polimer News - YouTube|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#Cases by districts|36]] of the [[List of districts of Tamil Nadu|38 districts]] are affected, with [[Chennai district|Chennai]] and [[Coimbatore district|Coimbatore]] being the worst-hit districts. As of 15 April, the state has the most number of coronavirus hotspots in India with 22 districts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/major-metros-in-hotspots-list-tamil-nadu-tops-with-most-11586979604010.html|title=Major metros in hotspots list, Tamil Nadu tops with most|date=2020-04-16|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> However, the mortality rate of 0.94% is among the lowest in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/covid-19-body-count-indias-low-mortality-rate-and-the-contrasting-pictures-of-two-states-2578653.html|title=Covid-19 Body Count: India's Low Mortality Rate and the Contrasting Pictures of Two States|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> As of 20 April, the infection rate has dropped from 13% on 1 April to 3.6%. As per the Health Department, 80% of the patients are asymptomatic while most deaths are among the elderly and those with co-morbidities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprint.in/health/tamil-nadu-is-containing-covid-19-well-and-it-is-not-following-bhilwara-model/403663/|title=Tamil Nadu is containing Covid-19 well, and it is not following Bhilwara model|last=Ch|first=Himani|last2=na|date=2020-04-17|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe state is under a [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]] since 25 March. The [[Government of Tamil Nadu|state government]] has responded to the outbreak by following a contact-tracing, testing and surveillance model.<ref name=\"containmentNews18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|title=Tamil Nadu Prepares for Stage Two of Coronavirus Outbreak With More Home Quarantines, Surveillance|website=News18|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329134259/https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{See also|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases chart}}\n\n{{Sidebar timeline\n| title = Major events in COVID19 pandemic in Tamil Nadu\n\n| years1 = '''07 March'''\n| color1 = tomato\n| events1 = First confirmed case\n\n| years2 = '''15 March'''\n| color2 = brown\n| events2 = Closure of commercial establishments, schools and colleges\n\n| years3 = '''20 March'''\n| color3 = brown\n| events3 = State borders closed\n\n| years4 = '''22 March'''\n| color4 = brown\n| events4 = Janta Curfew - Nation wide\n\n| years5 = '''24 March'''\n| color5 = brown\n| events5 = Section 144 imposed\n\n| years6 = '''25 March'''\n| color6 = black\n| events6 = First reported death <br> Nationwide lockdown imposed till 14 April\n\n| years7 = '''31 March'''\n| color7 = tomato\n| events7 = 100 confirmed cases <br> First case identified from Tablighi Jamaat cluster\n\n| years8 = '''11 April'''\n| color8 = black\n| events8 = 10 reported deaths\n\n| years9 = '''12 April'''\n| color9 = tomato\n| events9 = 1000 confirmed cases\n\n| years10 = '''14 April'''\n| color10 = brown\n| events10 = Nationwide lockdown extended till 3 May\n\n| years11 = '''15 April'''\n| color11 = blue\n| events11 = 100 reported recoveries\n\n| below =\n}}\n\n[[File:Corona Lockdown Tirupur, Tamil Nadu (2).jpg|thumb|Empty store shelves in [[Tiruppur]] due to panic buying prior to lockdown]]\n\n=== March ===\nThe first case of coronavirus was confirmed on 7 March in a resident from [[Kanchipuram]] in [[Chennai]]. He had returned from [[Oman]] and started developing symptoms including fever and cough.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-first-case-of-coronavirus-patient-quarantined-in-government-hospital-in-chennai/articleshow/74529929.cms?from=mdr|title=Tamil Nadu reports first case of Coronavirus; patient quarantined in Chennai Government Hospital|date=2020-03-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He was isolated in [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]]. Later, on 10 March, he recovered and tested negative.<ref name=\"TNrecovered\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-no-fresh-covid-19-cases-in-tamil-nadu-812479.html?utm_campaign=fullarticle&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=inshorts|title=Coronavirus: No fresh COVID-19 cases in Tamil Nadu|date=10 March 2020|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter more than a week without new cases, on 18 March, the second person who had travelled by train from Delhi to Chennai confirmed positive. He did not have any history of foreign travel and was described as a domestic case by the state health minister [[C. Vijayabaskar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil Nadu's 2nd Coronavirus patient raises community transmission fears|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319193205/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a 21-year-old student who returned from [[Ireland]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|title=Coronavirus LIVE: India's death toll rises to four|website=Business Standard|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319161417/https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, a further three were confirmed positive - A Chennai man who had travelled from [[New Zealand]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|title=Three more COVID-19 cases in State, one with no travel history|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324184127/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and two [[Thailand]] nationals in [[Erode]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-17-fresh-coronavirus-cases-tally-now-67-819262.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 17 fresh coronavirus cases; tally now 67|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> They were admitted to IRT Hospital in Perundurai in Erode. More than 300 people who had come in contact with the three patients were quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-7th-positive-coronavirus-case-816543.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 7th positive coronavirus case|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first virus-related death in the state was reported after a 54-year-old man in [[Madurai]] died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|title=\u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf : 54 \u0bb5\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0baa\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd {{!}} Patrikai - Tamil Daily - latest online local breaking news & reviews - Tamilnadu, India & World - politics, cinema, cricket, video & cartoon|date=2020-03-25|website=Tamil News patrikai {{!}} Tamil news online {{!}} latest tamil news|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328044912/https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Five others were infected - four Indonesians and their travel guide from Chennai.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-tally-goes-up-to-23/articleshow/74810591.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports five new coronavirus cases; tally goes up to 23|author=|newspaper=Economic Times|date = 26 March 2020}}</ref> The five were in quarantine since 22 March in Salem Medical College.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-reports-5-new-cases-covid-19-includes-4-indonesian-travellers-and-1-chennai-man-121103|title=TN reports 5 new cases of COVID-19, includes 4 Indonesian travellers and 1 Chennai man|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a 21-year-old youth who had just returned from a trip to [[Dublin]], Ireland was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-positive-tamil-nadu-man-with-travel-history-to-ireland-recovers-120032800122_1.html|title=Covid-19 positive Tamil Nadu man with travel history to Ireland recovers|author=|date=28 March 2020|newspaper=Business Standard India|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two new cases - one each in [[Kumbakonam]] and [[Katpadi]] were reported. With this, the total number of confirmed cases had reached 40 in the state.<ref name=\"28Bulletin\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328125841/https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the state reported eight more cases (four each from Coimbatore and Erode), all of which were linked to the two [[Thailand|Thai]] nationals and their group who had tested positive. The eight included a 10-month-old baby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|title=10-month-old baby and 7 more test positive for COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu; state's tally rises to 50|date=29 March 2020|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329142751/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|archive-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The total number of confirmed cases reached 50.<ref name=\"29Bulletin\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=29 March 2020|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070556/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, 17 new cases were reported, highest till date in the state<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> - 10 male patients from [[Erode]], all of whom have travelled to Delhi were in contact with the Thailand tourists, 5 in Chennai and 1 each in [[Karur]] and [[Madurai]].<ref name=\"MB-Mar30\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media_Bulletin_30_03_2020_5_Pages_English_226_KB-1.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_30_03_2020_5_Pages_English_226_KB-1.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414131304/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media_Bulletin_30_03_2020_5_Pages_English_226_KB-1.pdf|archive-date=14 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n[[File:Corona helmet of Chennai cop.jpg|alt=Chennai cop corona helmet|thumb|A police official in Chennai wearing a unique 'Corona' helmet to dissuade commuters from venturing out during the lockdown.]]\nOn 31 March, 57 new cases were reported, all with a history of travel predominately to [[Delhi]], bringing the total to 124.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-reports-57-new-covid-19-cases-in-one-day-79-attended-tablighi-jamaat-state-tally-at-124-1661904-2020-03-31|title=Tamil Nadu reports 57 new Covid-19 cases in one day, 79% attended Tablighi Jamaat. State tally at 124|date=|work=India Today|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the highest single day rise till date. 50 of these cases were from [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]] (18), [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]] (22), [[Kanyakumari district|Kanyakumari]] (4) [[Viluppuram|Villupuram]] (3), [[Madurai district|Madurai]] (2) and [[Thoothukudi district|Thoothukudi]] (1), all had travel history to Delhi.<ref name=\"31MarBulletin2\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070737/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Officials had discovered that at least 80 out of 124 confirmed cases (79 per cent) in Tamil Nadu were from one cluster as they are direct or indirect contact of the two Thai nationals who had tested positive for on 21 March.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /><ref name=\"Hindu-31March\" /> The Thai nationals, identified as patients 5 and 6 were part of a large group from countries including [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], etc. who had visited the state for an annual pilgrimage.<ref name=\"Hindu-31March\">{{Cite news|last=M|first=Serena Josephine|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|title=25 of 67 patients directly or indirectly linked to Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331163219/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This group had also attended a 3-day ''[[Tablighi Jamaat]]'' congregation in [[Nizamuddin Markaz Mosque|Nizamuddin Markaz mosque]], [[New Delhi]] in early March.<ref name=\"March31-DH\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-25-out-of-67-in-tamil-nadu-have-contact-or-travel-history-with-thai-nationals-819372.html|title=Coronavirus: 25 out of 67 in Tamil Nadu have contact or travel history with Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was estimated that more than 1,500 people from the state had participated in this event.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|title=Coimbatore, Erode Stare at Crisis as Tamil Nadu Govt Races to Trace Scores Back from Nizamuddin Event|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401020556/https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials also confirmed that the 54-year-old patient who had died the previous week had also participated in the gathering.  Of 1,500 people who were in the gathering, 1,130 had returned to the state. The government had identified and isolated 515 of the 1,130 people.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /> It faced difficulty while trying to map the rest. It had urged people who attended the gathering to step forward and get tested.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Coronavirus update: Tamil Nadu reports 50 more Covid-19 cases {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mar 31|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=23:31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331211819/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following this, the Nizamuddin Markaz emerged as a new virus hotspot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-nizamuddin-markaz-became-a-hotspot-for-covid-19-8-000-people-identified/story-zedKlaDNTPpbDLdMsgExAM.html|title=How Nizamuddin markaz became Covid-19 hotspot; more than 8,000 attendees identified|date=2020-04-02|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402162727/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-nizamuddin-markaz-became-a-hotspot-for-covid-19-8-000-people-identified/story-zedKlaDNTPpbDLdMsgExAM.html|archive-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\nOn 1 April, the state reported 110 new cases, all attended the Delhi Nizamuddin event. The total became 234.<ref name=\"MB-Apr1\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407060455/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media_Bulletin_01.04.2020_6_Pages_English_318_KB.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"April1-IT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-new-coronavirus-cases-linked-nizamuddin-event-tabligh-1662243-2020-04-01|title=Tamil Nadu reports 110 new coronavirus cases, all linked to Nizamuddin event|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TNM-TJ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|title=110 more cases in Tamil Nadu on Wednesday, all attended Delhi Jamaat conference|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402005422/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|archive-date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Health Secretary Beela Rajesh said that 1103  out of 1500 attendees of the event had been traced and isolated. 658 of their samples had been tested of which,190 tested positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu witnesses steep rise in cases|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401210601/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some of the participants approached officials themselves after government's request.<ref name=\"TNM-TJ\" /> Family members and close contacts were either taken to quarantine facilities or home quarantined.<ref name=\"TOI-TJcontainment\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/special-containment-plan-for-tj-group/articleshow/74939483.cms|title=Tamil Nadu: Special containment plan for Tablighi Jamaat group {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Apr 2|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=Ist|first3=08:57}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, 75 new cases were reported, of which 74 of them attended ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi.<ref name=\"MB_april02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_02_04_20_COVID_19_6_PM.pdf|title=Media Bulletin April 02|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, 102 new cases were reported, of which 100 were Delhi event participants. Two others were from Chennai, one with [[Comorbidity|co-morbid]] condition and one US-returnee.<ref name=\"MB-Apr3\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-03-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-03-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404185030/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-03-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=4 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, 74 new cases were reported, of which 69 were Delhi event participants, 4 were contacts of the event participants. One was from Chennai.<ref name=\"MB-Apr4\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-04-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-04-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414131307/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-04-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=14 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"TheHinduApr04\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/74-new-cases-take-tamil-nadus-total-to-485/article31259992.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} 74 new cases take Tamil Nadu's total to 485|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405032029/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/74-new-cases-take-tamil-nadus-total-to-485/article31259992.ece|archive-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> Two more deaths were reported, a 51 years old male who attended ''Tablighi Jamaat'' at Villupuram and a female at Theni Government hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/two-dead-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu/article31258200.ece#|title=Two dead of Covid-19 in Tamil Nadu|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407055948/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/two-dead-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu/article31258200.ece|archive-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, 86 new cases were reported of which 85 are related to Delhi event directly or indirectly. A 71 year old from Ramanathapuram who died on Thursday was tested positive. A 60 year old also died in the same hospital as previous patient.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sujatha|first=R.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tn-reports-86-more-covid-19-cases-total-spikes-to-571/article31263138.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Tamil Nadu reports 86 new cases, two more patients die|date=2020-04-05|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406035038/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tn-reports-86-more-covid-19-cases-total-spikes-to-571/article31263138.ece|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health department revealed that 1246 contacts of Tablighi Jamaat participants have been traced and isolated so far.<ref name=\"MB-Apr5\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-05-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-05-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405215542/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-05-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=5 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, 50 new cases were reported bringing the total cases to 621. 48 of them were returnees of Delhi event.<ref name=\"MB-Apr6\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-06-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-1.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-06-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-1.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406132432/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-06-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-1.pdf|archive-date=6 April 2020|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> 101 people who attended a COVID-19 victim's burial were home-quarantined in [[Ramanathapuram district|Ramanathapuram]]. They were not aware of his condition as the test result returned positive after only two days his burial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/06/over-100-quarantined-after-covid-19-victim-buried-without-precautions-in-tamil-nadu-2126260.html|title=Over 100 quarantined after COVID-19 victim buried without precautions in Tamil Nadu|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123052/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/06/over-100-quarantined-after-covid-19-victim-buried-without-precautions-in-tamil-nadu-2126260.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, 69 new cases were reported, of which 63 were related to Delhi event.<ref name=\"MB-Apr7\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-07-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-revised.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-07-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-revised.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407141921/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-07-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM-revised.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, 48 new cases were reported bringing total to 738. 42 of those are connected to ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi.<ref name=\"MB-8Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-08-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-08-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408133536/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-08-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=8 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> One among the 42 is a Malaysian national. Government had revealed that 1480 attendees of the Delhi event were traced and isolated. 1716 samples from them and their contacts were tested, of which 679 had returned positive.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/09/tamil-nadu-reports-48-new-covid19-cases-tally-climbs-to-738-2127606.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 48 new COVID19 cases, tally climbs to 738|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, the state reported 96 new cases which brought the total cases to 834.<ref name=\"MB-9Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin09.04.20-5-Pages-English-173-KB.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin09.04.20-5-Pages-English-173-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409140149/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin09.04.20-5-Pages-English-173-KB.pdf|archive-date=9 April 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April, 77 new cases were reported bringing total to 911. 70 of those are connected to ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi. 17 cases were clinically recovered, bringing the total recovered to 44.<ref name=\"MB-10Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-10-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-10-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411011448/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-10-04-20-COVID-19-6-PM.pdf|archive-date=11 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, 58 new cases were reported bringing the total to 969 of which, 47 belonged to the Delhi cluster.<ref name=\"MB-11Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-11.04.2020.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-11.04.2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> One more died in IRT Government Hospital at Perundurai in Erode, taking the death toll to 10. The state government revealed that it will decide on the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]] extension based on Centre's announcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-awaits-pms-announcement-on-lockdown-extension-reports-58-more-covid-19-cases-and-one-more-death/articleshow/75098435.cms|title=Tamil Nadu awaits PM\u2019s announcement on lockdown extension, reports 58 more Covid-19 cases and one more death {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mariappan|first=Julie|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412040333/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-awaits-pms-announcement-on-lockdown-extension-reports-58-more-covid-19-cases-and-one-more-death/articleshow/75098435.cms|archive-date=12 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, 106 new cases were reported bringing the total to 1075.<ref name=\"MB-12Apr\" >{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-12.04.2020-5-pages-English-178-KB.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-12.04.2020-5-pages-English-178-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412182422/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-12.04.2020-5-pages-English-178-KB.pdf|archive-date=12 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> One death was reported, a 45-year-old women died on previous day evening, she was undergoing treatment at a Government Hospital in Chennai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/13/covid-19-tamil-nadu-scales-1000-mark-93560-people-quarantined-for-28-days-2129281.html|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu scales 1000-mark, 93,560 people quarantined for 28 days|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413023709/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/13/covid-19-tamil-nadu-scales-1000-mark-93560-people-quarantined-for-28-days-2129281.html|archive-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The new infections were found in clusters in Chennai - where four were primary sources and Coimbatore - where two primary sources were identified. According to the health department, of the 106 new cases, 90 contracted the infection from them 16 people who had travel history.<ref name=\"Hindu-106cases\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-one-more-death-106-fresh-cases-in-tamil-nadu/article31325855.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} One more death, 106 fresh cases in Tamil Nadu|date=2020-04-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-13|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413065713/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-one-more-death-106-fresh-cases-in-tamil-nadu/article31325855.ece|archive-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April, 98 new cases were reported bringing the total to 1173.<ref name=\"MB-13Apr\" >{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-13.04.2020-5pages-English-181-KB.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-13.04.2020-5pages-English-181-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414095728/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-13.04.2020-5pages-English-181-KB.pdf|archive-date=14 April 2020|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, 31 new cases were reported bringing the total to 1204. It was the lowest daily rise since 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-lowest-daily-rise-in-covid-19-cases-since-march-31-missing-patient-secured/articleshow/75145246.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports lowest daily rise in Covid-19 cases since March 31; missing patient secured {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|last2=Marx|first2=Karal|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415054221/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-lowest-daily-rise-in-covid-19-cases-since-march-31-missing-patient-secured/articleshow/75145246.cms|archive-date=15 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> A 96-year-old died, making the total of 12 deaths in the state.<ref name=\"MB-14Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-14.04.2020-4-Pages-English-175-KB.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-14.04.2020-4-Pages-English-175-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, 38 new cases were reported in the state of which, 34 were related to Delhi cluster.<ref name=\"MB-15Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-15.04.2020.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-15.04.2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415135147/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-15.04.2020.pdf|archive-date=15 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> Deaths of two men were reported, a 47-year-old man with [[Influenza-like illness|SARI]] in [[Stanley Medical College|Stanley Government hospital]], Chennai and a 59-year-old man in a private hospital, making the total of 14 deaths in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/15/two-men-die-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-toll-now-14-1242-people-infected-2130568.html|title=Two men die of COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu, toll now 14; 1242 people infected|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, 25 new cases were reported bringing total to 1267. One death was reported making total of 15 deaths in the state<ref name=\"MB-16Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin16.04.2020.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin16.04.2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416154107/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin16.04.2020.pdf|archive-date=16 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, 56 new cases were reported which brought the total to 1323.<ref name=\"MB-17Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-17.04.2020.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-17.04.2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200417190133/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-17.04.2020.pdf|archive-date=17 April 2020|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 April, 49 new cases were reported which brought the total to 1372. 82 patients were discharged making total recovered cases as 365.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dinamalar.com/news_detail.asp?id=2523452 |title=\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe\u0bb5\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 1372 \u0baa\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bbe\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1; 15 \u0baa\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf&#124; Coronavirus cases in Tamil Nadu rise to 1372 |publisher=Dinamalar |date= |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\"MB-18Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-18.04.2020.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-18.04.2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April, 105 new cases were reported, third highest daily increase till date. 46 patients were discharged making total recovered cases as 411.<ref name=\"MB-19Apr\"/>\n\nOn 20 April, 43 new cases reported in Tamil Nadu bringing the total cases in Tamil Nadu to 1,520.<ref name=\"MB-20Apr\"/> The infection rate in the state had dropped from 13% on 1 April 2020 to 3.6% .<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dubey|first=Jyotindra|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/covid-19-delhi-has-highest-infection-rate-tamil-nadu-is-showing-recovery-120042000685_1.html|title=Covid-19: Delhi has highest infection rate, Tamil Nadu is showing recovery|date=2020-04-20|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April, 33 new cases reported in Tamil Nadu bringing the total cases to 1,629. 27 patients were discharged making total discharged to 662. No death were reported for the day <ref>https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-22.04.2020.pdf</ref>\n\nOn 23 April, Dharmapuri reported its First COVID-19 patient, 54 new cases were reported in Tamil Nadu bringing the total cases to 1,683. 90 patients were discharged making total discharged to 752. 2 fatality for the day and which brings the total to 20.<ref name=\"MB-23Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media-Bulletin-23.04.2020.pdf|title=Media-Bulletin-23.04.2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Cases ==\nThe data below are based on Health and Family Welfare Department of Tamil Nadu daily reports.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases}}\n\n=== Cases by districts ===\n<div style=\"display: flex; width: 100%;\">\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases by district}}\n</div>\n\n==== Districts without confirmed cases ====\nThe following districts have not reported any cases and are classified as 'Green' zones.<ref name=\"TOI-zones\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-wants-lockdown-extended-by-two-weeks-but-will-await-pm-modis-call/articleshow/75106907.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Lockdown: Tamil Nadu wants lockdown extended by two weeks, but will await PM Modi\u2019s call {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mariappan|first=Julie|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413154126/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-wants-lockdown-extended-by-two-weeks-but-will-await-pm-modis-call/articleshow/75106907.cms|archive-date=13 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n* [[Krishnagiri district|Krishnagiri]]\n* [[Mayiladuthurai district|Mayiladuthurai]]\n\n== Testing ==\nThe government started screening passengers arriving at the airports in January. It had screened 2,10,538 passengers as of 1 April. As of 16 April, More than 1 lakh passengers have been placed under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNIE-0case\" />\n\nBy 16 March, following [[Indian Council of Medical Research|ICMR]]'s guidelines to test for community transmission, the state had tested 22 random samples of people with [[influenza]] and severe acute respiratory infection (SARI) for [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|coronavirus]]. All tested negative.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\">{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|title=Why Kerala has done more coronavirus tests than Tamil Nadu \u2013 and why this must change|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328121533/https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> By 10 April, of 577 SARI patients tested, five were positive.<ref name=\"SARI-10Apr\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-india-second-icmr-report-random-sampling-test-results-shows-possible-community-transmission-1665290-2020-04-10|title=Coronavirus: Second ICMR report on random sampling test results shows possible community transmission|last=DelhiApril 10|first=Milan Sharma New|last2=April 10|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Ist|first3=2020 10:17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412160840/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-india-second-icmr-report-random-sampling-test-results-shows-possible-community-transmission-1665290-2020-04-10|archive-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Testing rates ===\nDuring the first half of March, the state faced criticism for the low number of tests. By 16 March, it had only tested 90 samples while neighbouring Kerala and Karnataka had tested more than 1500 and 750 samples.<ref name=\"Testing-TOI\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|title=Coronavirus Tamil Nadu Updates: In Tamil Nadu, patients &amp; doctors call for increased tests on coronavirus {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=16 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321071302/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|archive-date=21 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31|agency=TNN}}</ref> The director of Public Health defended the state's low number of tests by saying that Kerala saw more travel from coronavirus-affected countries which is why it had detected more cases.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\" /> The Public Health department had also said that the state follows test protocols established by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Union Health Ministry]].<ref name=\"scroll-tests\" /><ref name=\"Testing-TOI\" /> Following the Delhi Nizamuddin event, the families of all identified participants were tested regardless of whether they showed symptoms or not.<ref name=\"TOI-TJcontainment\" />\n\nTamil Nadu has the highest the percentage of positive samples among total samples tested in the country at 13% as of 7 April. This has been attributed to detection of cases related to the Tablighi Jamaat gathering in Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiaspend.com/13-of-samples-in-tamil-nadu-are-testing-positive-4-in-india/|title=13% of samples in Tamil Nadu are testing positive, 4% in India {{!}}|last=Raman|first=Shreya|date=2020-04-08|website=www.indiaspend.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413054301/https://www.indiaspend.com/13-of-samples-in-tamil-nadu-are-testing-positive-4-in-india/|archive-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, the health officials of the state said that they have changed the testing strategy to \u201caggressive testing\u201d, also including asymptomatic individuals.<ref name=\"DNext-12Apr2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/12183523/1224770/Tamil-Nadu-crosses-1000mark-in-coronavirus-cases.vpf|title=Tamil Nadu COVID-19 cases cross 1000, eight doctors contract virus|last=100010509524078|date=2020-04-12|website=dtNext.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The Health Secretary also said the state is looking to employ the 24,000 real time  [[Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction|Reverse-Transcription Polymerase Chain Reaction]] (RT-PCR) test kits that it has in possession for more stringent testing. \u201cOur strategy is to ramp up testing using RT-PCR kits. These testing kits are of the gold standard and their results are completely reliable. We will use the RT-PCR test kits to aggressively test primary and secondary contacts.\" the official said.<ref name=\"DH-13Apr2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/coronavirus-with-over-1000-cases-tn-changes-testing-strategy-825043.html|title=Coronavirus: With over 1,000 cases, TN changes testing strategy|date=2020-04-13|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The move was welcomed health professionals. Many politicians and media persons have reiterated WHOs advice of \"test, test and test\".\n\nOn 14 April, the Chennai Corporation revealed that it plans to collect 40,000 swab samples, including 10,000 from containment zones. It has set up 35 walk-in kiosks for the purpose.<ref name=\"TNM-tradecenter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/trade-centre-chennai-converted-550-bed-covid-19-quarantine-ward-122629 |title=Trade centre in Chennai converted into a 550-bed COVID-19 quarantine ward |website=www.thenewsminute.com|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Rapid test kits ===\nOn 6 April after ICMR's approval, the state government placed an independent order to purchase around one lakh serology-based [[Rapid diagnostic test|rapid test kits]] from China, that can return quick results and are expected to be used for mass testing in smaller towns and rural areas.<ref name=\"HT-response2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/5-lessons-from-tamil-nadu-s-book-how-the-state-is-fighting-covid-19/story-Sl4kD5HZksOIuOTRDm2OeM.html|title=5 lessons from Tamil Nadu\u2019s book: How the state is fighting Covid-19|date=2020-04-07|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407165126/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/5-lessons-from-tamil-nadu-s-book-how-the-state-is-fighting-covid-19/story-Sl4kD5HZksOIuOTRDm2OeM.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"DH-13Apr2\"/> They were expected to be delivered by 9 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/06155451/1223661/1-lakh-rapid-test-kits-to-speed-up-COVID19-screening-.vpf|title=Tamil Nadu to deploy 1 lakh rapid test kits to speed up COVID-19 screening|last=100010509524078|date=2020-04-06|website=dtNext.in|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407044426/https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/06155451/1223661/1-lakh-rapid-test-kits-to-speed-up-COVID19-screening-.vpf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>  On 11 April, the Chief Secretary K Shanmugam said that the consignment meant for India was reportedly diverted to the [[United States]], causing delay.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rapid-testing-not-arrived-yet-consignment-diverted-us-tamil-nadu-chief-secy-1665964-2020-04-11|title=Rapid testing haven't arrived yet, consignment diverted to US: Tamil Nadu chief secy|last=ChennaiApril 11|first=Akshaya Nath|last2=April 11|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12|last3=Ist|first3=2020 21:09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412071909/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rapid-testing-not-arrived-yet-consignment-diverted-us-tamil-nadu-chief-secy-1665964-2020-04-11|archive-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The delay affected the testing rate of the state. The director of public health K Kolandaswamy said \"It is admittedly one of our biggest weakness, but we decided there is no point in waiting for the kits. We have to use every minute in this period resourcefully.\" Instead of waiting, the health department has decided to use the existing RT-PCR kits for mass screening.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/why-tamil-nadu-has-to-do-more-with-less/articleshow/75114082.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Lockdown: Why Tamil Nadu has to do more with less {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414131951/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/why-tamil-nadu-has-to-do-more-with-less/articleshow/75114082.cms|archive-date=14 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nAfter several delays, 24,000 rapid test kits reached Chennai on 17 April.<ref name=\"24kRTK\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-gets-24000-rapid-testing-kits-from-china/articleshow/75194586.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Corona News: Tamil Nadu gets 24,000 rapid testing kits from China {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> The state aims to use it for initial testing of close contacts of people who have tested positive and in areas around the containment zones.<ref name=\"HT-rapid\" /> If tested positive, their samples are sent for a confirmatory PCR test.<ref name=\"24kRTK\" /> The state had also ordered an additional 5 lakh rapid test kits and 1 lakh RT-PCR kits.<ref name=\"HT-rapid\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/with-400-000-kits-tn-to-ramp-up-testing/story-GyQ1gZbOr9oVumdeagzK3M.html|title=Coronavirus update: With 400,000 kits, Tamil Nadu to ramp up Covid-19 testing|date=2020-04-11|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412233926/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/with-400-000-kits-tn-to-ramp-up-testing/story-GyQ1gZbOr9oVumdeagzK3M.html|archive-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"DC-CM17apr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/170420/dip-in-new-cases-makes-tamil-nadu-chief-minister-highly-optimistic.html|title=Dip in new cases makes Tamil Nadu chief minister highly optimistic|last=Venkatesh|first=D. Sekar & M. R.|date=2020-04-17|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nChief Minister E Palaniswami had urged Prime Minister Narendra Modi to provide COVID-19 rapid test kits and {{INRConvert|1000|c}} immediately to procure medical supplies in a video-conference chaired by Modi and attended by the Chief Ministers of other states on 11 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ramakrishnan|first=T.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tamil-nadu-chief-minister-urges-prime-minister-modi-to-provide-covid-19-rapid-test-kits-1000-crore-immediately/article31317569.ece|title=Tamil Nadu Chief Minister urges Prime Minister Modi to provide COVID-19 rapid test kits, \u20b91,000 crore immediately|date=2020-04-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412074759/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tamil-nadu-chief-minister-urges-prime-minister-modi-to-provide-covid-19-rapid-test-kits-1000-crore-immediately/article31317569.ece|archive-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Testing facilities ===\nInitially, the state only had four government labs for conducting tests for the coronavirus.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\" /> As of 18 April, the state has 31 laboratories (21 government and 10 private) approved by ICMR for testing.<ref name=\"MB-18Apr\" /> According to reports, private labs has fixed a rate of Rs 4,500 for testing a COVID-19 sample. The state government had announced that it will bear all the expenses.<ref name=\"DNext-12Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/12183523/1224770/Tamil-Nadu-crosses-1000mark-in-coronavirus-cases.vpf|title=Tamil Nadu COVID-19 cases cross 1000, eight doctors contract virus|last=100010509524078|date=2020-04-12|website=dtNext.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==== Operational testing facilities ====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===== Public =====\n* [[Coimbatore Medical College]], [[Coimbatore]]\n* [[Government Dharmapuri Medical College]], [[Dharmapuri]]\n* [[Kilpauk Medical College|Government Kilpauk Medical College]], [[Chennai]]\n* [[Mohan Kumaramangalam Medical College|Government Mohan Kumaramangalam Medical College and Hospital]], [[Salem, Tamil Nadu|Salem]]\n* [[Stanley Medical College|Government Stanley Medical College and Hospital]], [[Chennai]] <sup>\u00a7</sup>\n* [[Theni Medical College|Government Theni Medical College]], [[Theni]]\n* [[Thoothukudi Medical College|Government Thoothukudi Medical College]], [[Thoothukudi]]\n* Government Tiruvarur Medical College, [[Thiruvarur|Tiruvarur]]\n* [[Government Vellore Medical College]], [[Vellore]]\n* [[Government Villupuram Medical College|Government Villupuram Medical College and Hospital]], [[Villupuram]]\n* Institute of Vector Control and Zoonoses, [[Krishnagiri]]\n* [[Government Erode Medical College|IRT Perundurai Medical College and Hospital, Perundurai]]\n* [[K.A.P.Viswanatham Government Medical College]], [[Tiruchirapalli]]\n* [[Kanyakumari Government Medical College]], [[Nagercoil]]\n* [[King Institute of Preventive Medicine and Research]] [[Chennai]]\n* [[Madras Medical College]], [[Chennai]]\n* [[Madurai Medical College]], [[Madurai]]\n* [[Pasteur Institute of India]], [[The Nilgiris district|Nilgiris]]\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Government General 