5\n | issue       = 1\n | pages       = 8\u201338\n | url         = https://byustudies.byu.edu/content/faithful-band-moses-mahlangu-and-first-soweto-saints\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===Other===\n*{{Cite thesis\n | author        = Turley, Theodore\n | editor        = Turley, Richard E. Jr\n | title         = Theodore Turley: Mission Journal, 1839-1840\n | publisher     = [[Brigham Young University]]\n | location      = Provo, Utah\n | year          = 1982\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n | author        = Turley, Ida Elizabeth Eyring\n | editor        = Turley, Richard E. Jr\n | title         = The Diary of Ida Elizabeth Eyring Turley: 1874-1952\n | publisher     = [[s.n.]]\n | location      = Salt Lake City\n | year          = 1997\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n | title         = Selected Collections from the Archives of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints\n | editor1-last  = Turley\n | editor1-first = Richard E. Jr\n |type=electronic resource, 2 volumes\n | publisher     = [[Brigham Young University Press]]\n | location      = Provo, Utah\n | year          = 2002\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n | author        = Turley, Richard E. Jr\n | title         = Why Can't I Forget My Sins?\n |type=sound recording\n | year          = 2006\n | publisher     = [[Deseret Book]]\n | location      = Salt Lake City, Utah\n | isbn          = 1-59038-553-5\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n2003-93778}}\n* [http://josephsmithpapers.org/projectTeam Biography] at Joseph Smith Papers Project website (accessed May 4, 2012)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turley, Richard E., Jr.}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mormon missionaries]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:American Latter Day Saint writers]]\n[[Category:American Mormon missionaries in Japan]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Utah]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mormon apologists]]\n[[Category:Official historians of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Worth, Texas]]\n[[Category:Writers from Salt Lake City]]\n[[Category:J. Reuben Clark Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Texas]]\n", "name_user": "Trappist the monk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBooks:cite repair;", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_E._Turley_Jr."}
{"title_page": "Oklahoma State University\u2013Stillwater", "text_new": "{{redirect|Oklahoma State University|other system schools|Oklahoma State University System}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Oklahoma State University\u2013Stillwater\n| image_name = Oklahoma State University seal.svg\n| image_upright = 0.7\n| established = {{start date|1890|12|25}}\n| type =[[Flagship university|Flagship]]<br />[[Public university|Public]]<br />[[Land-grant university|Land-grant]]<br />[[Space-grant university|Space-grant]] \n| affiliation = Oklahoma Agricultural & Mechanical Colleges\n| academic_affiliation= {{unbulleted list|[[Oklahoma State University System|OSU System]]|[[Association of Public and Land-Grant Universities|APLU]]|[[Oak Ridge Associated Universities|ORAU]]}}\n| endowment = $756.5 million (2019)<ref>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2019-Endowment-Market-Values--Final-Feb-10.ashx? |title=U.S. and Canadian 2019 NTSE Participating Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2019 Endowment Market Value, and Percentage Change in Market Value from FY18 to FY19 (Revised) |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| city = [[Stillwater, Oklahoma|Stillwater]]\n| state = [[Oklahoma]]\n| country = United States\n| coor = {{coord|36|07|56|N|97|04|51|W|type:edu_region:US-OK|display=inline,title}}\n| president = [[V. Burns Hargis]]\n| enrollment = 25,295<ref name=\"Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education\">{{cite web |url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=207388 |title=Oklahoma State University - Main Campus |publisher=Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education |date=2017 |accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| staff = 1,857\n| campus = [[City|Small city]], {{convert|1489|acre|km2}} on the Stillwater campus<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vpaf.okstate.edu/bam/Space/History.htm |title=History and Background Information \u2013 Budget & Asset Management \u2013 Oklahoma State University |publisher=Vpaf.okstate.edu |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720020634/http://vpaf.okstate.edu/bam/Space/History.htm |archivedate=July 20, 2011}}</ref>\n| colors = Orange and Black<ref>{{cite web|title=Oklahoma State University's Official Colors|url=https://brand.okstate.edu/site-files/documents/osu_colors.jpg|date=July 1, 2019 |accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref><br />{{college color boxes|Oklahoma State Cowboys}}\n| nickname = [[Oklahoma State Cowboys and Cowgirls|Cowboys and Cowgirls]]\n| sporting_affiliations = [[NCAA Division I]] \u2013 [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]]\n| mascot = [[Pistol Pete (Oklahoma State University)|Pistol Pete]]\n| website = {{url|go.okstate.edu}}\n| logo = Oklahoma State University system logo.svg\n| logo_upright = .7\n}}\n\n'''Oklahoma State University''' ('''OSU''') is a [[Public university|public]] [[land-grant university|land-grant]] [[research university]] in [[Stillwater, Oklahoma]]. OSU was founded in 1890 under the [[Morrill Act]]. Originally known as '''Oklahoma Agricultural and Mechanical College''' ('''Oklahoma A&M'''), it is the flagship institution of the [[Oklahoma State University System]]. Official enrollment for the fall 2010 semester system-wide was 35,073, with 23,459<ref name=\"newsok.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2014_Endowment_Market_Values_Revised.pdf |title=2014 Endowment Market Value |publisher=nacubo.org |date=June 30, 2014 |accessdate=March 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223091003/http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2014_Endowment_Market_Values_Revised.pdf |archive-date=February 23, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> students enrolled at OSU-Stillwater. Enrollment shows the Freshman class of 2012 was the largest on record with 4,298 students.<ref name=\"newsok.com\"/> OSU is classified by the [[Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching|Carnegie Foundation]] as a research university with highest research activity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=207388 |title=Carnegie Foundation \u2013 Oklahoma State University \u2013 Main Campus |publisher=Carnegiefoundation.org |year=2010 |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Oklahoma State Cowboys and Cowgirls]]' athletic heritage includes 52 national championships, a total greater than all but three [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] schools in the United States, and first in the [[Big 12 Conference]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/champs_records_book/summaries/Men.pdf |title=NCAA Summary, National Collegiate/Division I Men's |format=PDF |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627170857/http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/champs_records_book/summaries/Men.pdf |archivedate=June 27, 2010 }}</ref>  Students spend part of the fall semester preparing for OSU's Homecoming celebration, begun in 1913, which draws more than 40,000 alumni and over 70,000 participants each year to campus and is billed by the university as \"America's Greatest Homecoming Celebration.\"<ref name=\"orangeconnection.org\">{{cite web|url=http://orangeconnection.org/s/860/homecoming-interior.aspx?sid=860&gid=1&pgid=3768 |title=OSU Alumni Association \u2013 Homecoming History |publisher=Orangeconnection.org |date=October 30, 1920 |accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Old Central.jpg|thumb|left|[[Old Central]] at Oklahoma A&M, 1894]]\n[[File:Williams-Hall-Library-OKStateU-formerlyAM-Stillwater.jpg|thumb|Williams Hall, the Castle of the Prairies, in 1920]]\nOn December 25, 1890, the [[Oklahoma territory|Oklahoma Territorial]] Legislature finally gained approval for '''Oklahoma Territorial Agricultural and Mechanical (A&M) College''', the [[land-grant]] university established under the Morrill Act of 1862. It specified that the college was to be within [[Payne County, Oklahoma|Payne County]]. Such an ambiguous description created rivalry between towns within the county, with Stillwater ultimately winning out. Upon statehood in 1907, \"Territorial\" was dropped from its title.\n[[File:OklahomaA&MSeal.png|thumb|left|Oklahoma A&M seal]]\nThe first students assembled for class on December 14, 1891. Classes were held for two and one-half years in local churches until the first academic building, later known as [[Old Central]], was dedicated on June 15, 1894, on the southeast corner of campus, which at the time was flat plowed prairie.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.library.okstate.edu/scua/exhibit/campusbeg/index.htm |title=Campus Beginnings: 1890\u20131940 \u2013 SCUA Online Exhibit \u2013 OSU Library |publisher=Library.okstate.edu |date=January 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101230515/http://www.library.okstate.edu/scua/exhibit/campusbeg/index.htm |archivedate=January 1, 2011}}</ref> In 1896, '''Oklahoma A&M''' held its first commencement with six male graduates. The first Library was established in Old Central in one room shared with the English Department.  The first campus building to have electricity, Williams Hall, was constructed in 1900. With its turreted architecture it was referred to as the \"Castle of the Prairies\";<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.library.okstate.edu/about/history.htm |title=OSU Library History |publisher=Library.okstate.edu |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324062655/http://www.library.okstate.edu/about/history.htm |archive-date=March 24, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> It remained standing until 1969. One of the earliest campus buildings was also a barn, used as part of an agricultural experiment station, which was served by a large reservoir pond created in 1895.  The barn burned in 1922, but the pond, enlarged and remodeled in 1928 and 1943, is now known as Theta Pond, a popular campus scenic landmark.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.library.okstate.edu/scua/exhibit/theta/index.htm |title=Special Collections: Theta Pond |publisher=Library.okstate.edu |date=September 22, 2008 |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110102101236/http://www.library.okstate.edu/scua/exhibit/theta/index.htm |archivedate=January 2, 2011}}</ref> In 1906, Morrill Hall was completed and became the principal building on campus. A fire gutted the building in 1914, but the outside structure survived intact, and the interior was reconstructed.\n\n[[File:Oklahoma A&M Boys Dormitory.jpg|thumb|left|Boy's Dormitory, later Crutchfield Hall]]\nOn-campus housing at Oklahoma A&M College began in 1910, with the opening of the Boy's Dormitory.<ref name=dorm>{{cite web|title=OSU Housing and Residential Life celebrates centennial|date=October 18, 2010|publisher=Oklahoma State Housing and Residential Life|url=https://news.okstate.edu/articles/communications/2010/osu-housing-and-residential-life-celebrates-centennial.html|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref> Later renamed Crutchfield Hall, the [[Historic American Buildings Survey]] said it was significant as \"... the first permanent boy's dormitory in Oklahoma ... [and] the sole surviving example of a pre-1930 utilitarian dormitory that is characteristic of modified Italian Renaissance Revival architecture\".<ref>{{cite web|title=\nOklahoma State University, Boys Dormitory, Northwest corner of Hester Street & Athletic Avenue, Stillwater, Payne County, OK|publisher=[[Historic American Buildings Survey]]|url=https://www.loc.gov/pictures/collection/hh/item/ok0069/|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref> Crutchfield Hall later served the School of Music and the College of Engineering, Architecture, and Technology before its demolition in 1955.<ref name=dorm /> Also opened in 1910 was the Women's Building, containing a dining hall, home economics classes, and a women's gymnasium, in addition to resident housing for female students. It was later named Garner Hall and survives to the present day as the Bartlett Center for the Studio Arts and houses the Gardiner Art Gallery.<ref name=dorm /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://art.okstate.edu/facilities/gardiner.php |title=Facilities // Oklahoma State University Department of Art |publisher=Art.okstate.edu |accessdate=October 26, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504150420/http://art.okstate.edu/facilities/gardiner.php |archivedate=May 4, 2015}}</ref> By 1919 the campus included Morrill Hall, the Central Building, the Engineering Building (now [[Gundersen Hall]]), the Women's building, the Auditorium (replaced later by the Seretean Center for Performing Arts),<ref>[http://music.okstate.edu/sereteancenter.php] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604122454/http://music.okstate.edu/sereteancenter.php|date=June 4, 2010}}</ref> the Armory-Gymnasium (now the Architecture Building) and the Power Plant.<ref>[A History of the Oklahoma State University Campus, by J. Lewie Sanderson, R. Dean McGlamery, and David C. Peters]</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of [[World War II]], Oklahoma A&M was one of six schools selected by the [[United States Navy]] to give the Primary School in the [[Electronics Training Program]] (ETP), also known as Naval Training School Elementary Electricity and Radio Materiel (NTS EE&RM).<ref>[http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/ref/USN-Act/OK.html%20US%20Naval%20Activities%20WWII%20By%20State]{{dead link|date=October 2015}}</ref> Starting in March 1942, each month a new group of 100 Navy students arrived for three months of 14-hour days in concentrated electrical engineering study. Cordell Hall, the newest dormitory, was used for housing and meals; lectures and lab sessions were held in the Engineering Building. Professor Emory B. Phillips was the Director of Instruction. ETP admission required passing the [[Eddy Test]], one of the most selective qualifying exams given during the war years.<ref>Test and Research Staff, Bureau of Naval Personnel; \u201cPsychological test construction and research in the Bureau of Naval Personnel. Part V. Navy radio technician training program\u201d; ''American Psychologist'', vol 1(3), Mar. 1946, pp 80-90</ref> At a given time, some 500 Navy students were on the campus, a significant fraction of the war-years enrollment. The training activity continued until June 1945, and served a total of about 7,000 students; among these was [[Robert B. Kamm]], a future professor and president of Oklahoma State University.<ref>Naeter, Albrecht; \"Naval Training School,\" ''The Oklahoma State Engineer'', Dec. 1943</ref><ref>Watson, Raymond C., Jr.; ''Solving the Naval Radar Crisis'', Trafford Publishing, 2007, pp. 208-211, {{ISBN|978-1-4251-6173-6}}</ref> During some of the war years, the Navy also had a [[Yeoman (US Navy)|Yeoman]] training activity for [[WAVES]] and [[SPARS]] on the campus.\n[[File:Student Union - Oklahoma State University.jpg|thumb|Student Union Building at OSU]]\nMuch of the growth of Oklahoma A&M and the campus architectural integrity can be attributed to work of [[Henry G. Bennett]], who served as the school's president from 1928 to 1950. Early in his tenure Dr. Bennett developed a strategic vision for the physical expansion of the university campus. The plan was adopted in 1937 and his vision was followed for more than fifty years, making the university what it is today, including the [[Georgian architecture]] that permeates the campus. The focal point of his vision was a centrally located library building, which became a reality when the [[Edmon Low Library]] opened in 1953. Another major addition to the campus during the Bennett years was the construction of the Student Union, which opened in 1950. Subsequent additions and renovations have made the building one of the largest student union buildings in the world at {{convert|611000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://union.okstate.edu/renovation/BuildingHistory.htm |title=OSU Student Union Building History |publisher=Union.okstate.edu |date=September 9, 1950 |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720020635/http://union.okstate.edu/renovation/BuildingHistory.htm |archivedate=July 20, 2011}}</ref> A complete renovation and further expansion of the building began in 2010.\n\n[[File:HenryBennettStatueatOSU.jpg|thumb|left|Statue of Henry G. Bennett near Library Lawn at OSU]]\nOn May 15, 1957, '''Oklahoma A&M''' changed its name '''Oklahoma State University of Agricultural and Applied Sciences''' to reflect the broadening scope of curriculum offered. Oklahoma Gov. [[Raymond Gary]] signed the bill authorizing the name change passed by the 26th Oklahoma Legislature on May 15, 1957. However, the bill only authorized the Board of Regents to change the name of the college, a measure they voted on at their meeting on June 6. However, the name was quickly shortened to '''Oklahoma State University''' for most purposes, and the \"Agricultural & Applied Sciences\" name was formally dropped in 1980. Subsequently, the [[Oklahoma State University System]] was created, with the Stillwater campus as the flagship institution and several outlying branches: [[Oklahoma State University - Okmulgee|OSU-Institute of Technology]] in [[Okmulgee, OK|Okmulgee]] (1946), [[Oklahoma State University - Oklahoma City|OSU-Oklahoma City]] (1961), [[Oklahoma State University - Tulsa|OSU-Tulsa]] (1984), and the [[Oklahoma State University - Center for Health Sciences|Center for Health Sciences]] also in [[Tulsa]] (1988).<ref>[http://osu.okstate.edu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=280&Itemid=96 \"OSU History\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901073919/http://osu.okstate.edu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=280&Itemid=96 |date=September 1, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, OSU announced its \"Campus Master Plan\", a campaign to enhance academic, athletic, and administrative facilities. Over $800 million is ear-marked for campus construction and renovation over twenty years. The Plan calls for an \"athletic village\" where all of the university's athletic facilities will be located on the main campus. To accomplish this goal, the athletic department bought all (or nearly all) the property north of [[Boone Pickens Stadium]] up to McElroy between Knoblock and Washington streets. This drew criticism from the city of Stillwater and property owners.<ref>{{cite web | title=Pickens's Donation to Oklahoma State Spurs Fight on Land Grab | work=Boone State | url=http://clerestoryav.com/boonestate/bloomberg.html | accessdate=May 24, 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008110609/http://clerestoryav.com/boonestate/bloomberg.html | archivedate=October 8, 2007 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>  While the vast majority of the real estate was rental property targeting college students, a few owners were longtime residents. There was a lone holdout in this parcel of land, who sued OSU over their right to use [[eminent domain]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Lone Holdout Blocks Pickens's Vast Sports Project at Oklahoma State U. | work=The Chronicle of Higher Education | url=http://chronicle.com/news/article/1063/lone-holdout-blocks-pickenss-vast-sports-project-at-oklahoma-state-u| accessdate=May 24, 2007}}</ref> The case was decided in favor of the University. The project includes the construction of an indoor practice facility for most sports, a soccer stadium/outdoor track, a tennis complex, and a baseball stadium.\n[[File:Edmon Low Library - Oklahoma State University.jpg|thumb|right|Edmon Low Library]]\nIn 2006, OSU became the recipient of a gift of $165 million from alumnus [[T. Boone Pickens]] to the university's athletic department, and in 2008 received another gift from Pickens of $100 million for endowed academic chairs.  It was the largest gift for academics ever given in the state.<ref>[http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/052208dnmetpickens.152d3ba1.html Dallas Morning News, \"T. Boone Pickens donates $100M to OSU\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907043832/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/052208dnmetpickens.152d3ba1.html |date=September 7, 2008 }}</ref>  Ethical concerns have been raised in media reports about the propriety of how some of the Pickens gifts have been made, immediately returned to Pickens, and then placed in hedge funds owned by Pickens' companies<ref>{{cite news|last=Gose|first=Ben|title=Concerns are Raised about how Oklahoma State U Handled a Gift |url=http://chronicle.com/article/Concerns-Are-Raised-About-How/1287/|newspaper=Chronicle of Higher Education|date=October 30, 2008}}</ref>  In February 2010, Pickens announced that he was pledging another $100 million to fund a scholarship endowment as part of a $1 billion fund-raising campaign titled \"Branding Success.\" The pledge brought the total pledged or contributed to OSU by Pickens to over $500 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/with-t.-boone-pickens-gift-osu-kicks-off-drive-for-1b/article/3442701 |title=NewsOK, \"With T. Boone Pickens\u2019 gift, OSU kicks off drive for $1B\" |publisher=Newsok.com |date=February 27, 2010 |accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 2015 during the annual homecoming parade, Adacia Chambers [[2015 Oklahoma State University homecoming parade crash|drove her vehicle into a crowd of people]] killing 4 people and injuring 47.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/woman-faces-2nd-degree-murder-charges-in-oklahoma-crash/ar-BBmoHa8?li=AAa0dzB&ocid=mailsignout|title=Woman faces 2nd-degree murder charges in Oklahoma crash|publisher=Msn.com|accessdate=October 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029003114/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/woman-faces-2nd-degree-murder-charges-in-oklahoma-crash/ar-BBmoHa8?li=AAa0dzB&ocid=mailsignout|archive-date=October 29, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Colleges ==\nOklahoma State University\u2013Stillwater offers nearly 200 undergraduate degree majors through six Colleges:\n* Ferguson College of Agriculture (Previously the College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources)\n* College of Arts and Sciences\n* College of Education, Health, and Aviation\n* College of Engineering, Architecture, and Technology\n* College of Human Sciences\n* Spears School of Business\n\nOSU provides further opportunities for select students to study, conduct research, and exchange ideas in a more challenging and supportive academic environment through the Honors College.\n\nThe graduate degree programs of all colleges are administered through the Graduate College.\n\nThe Center for Veterinary Health Sciences (CVHS) has three academic Departments: Veterinary Pathobiology, Physiological Sciences, and Veterinary Clinical Sciences. Each of the three academic departments share responsibility for the four-year professional curriculum leading to the [[Doctor of Veterinary Medicine]] (D.V.M.) degree. The interdepartmental Veterinary Biomedical Sciences graduate program offers MS and PhD degrees. It also offers ECFVG and PAVE programmes for foreign trained veterinarians.\n\n==Rankings and reputation==\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| ARWU_W = 501\u2013600\n| ARWU_N = 138\u2013155\n| THE_WSJ = 373\n| Forbes = 358\n| QS_W = 751\u2013800\n| THES_W = 401\u2013500\n| USNWR_W = 493\n| USNWR_NU = 192\n| Wamo_NU = 153\n}}\nAs a land-grant university, OSU has several historically renowned programs, including the College of [[Agricultural]] Sciences and Natural Resources and the College of [[Veterinary Medicine]]. The College of Engineering is renowned in the fields of architecture and mechanical engineering. The School of Entrepreneurship is internationally renowned at both the practical and academic levels.\n*It has been named a ''Truman Honor Institution'' for its success in producing [[Harry S. Truman Scholarship|Truman scholars]].<ref>[http://okcbusiness.com/business_people_view.asp?pID=876 OKCBusiness \u2013 Oklahoma City Business News] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403121550/http://okcbusiness.com/business_people_view.asp?pID=876 |date=April 3, 2008 }}</ref>\n*OSU is one of five U.S. universities where [[Sun Grant Research Initiative]] programs have been established by the U.S. Congress in the Sun Grant Research Initiative Act of 2003 for the purposes of researching and developing sustainable and environmentally-friendly bio-based energy alternatives.\n*The Math Department has been recognized by the American Mathematics Association as one of four innovative programs in the nation and has produced four [[Sloan Fellowship]] winners.<ref>https://sloan.org/past-fellows</ref>\n*The [[Oklahoma Mesonet]], a state-of-the-art network of [[Biosphere|environmental monitoring]] stations that is an [[University of Oklahoma|OU]]-OSU partnership, won a special award from the [[American Meteorological Society]] (AMS), the nation's leading professional society for those in the atmospheric and related sciences at the [[National Weather Center]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mesonet.org/index.php/okfirst/program_history | title=Program Timeline | publisher=mesonet.org | accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref>\n*OSU is headquarters for the [[International Ground Source Heat Pump Association]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.igshpa.okstate.edu/about/about_us.htm |title=What is IGSHPA? |publisher=Igshpa.okstate.edu |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404051034/http://www.igshpa.okstate.edu/about/about_us.htm |archive-date=April 4, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which has members from as far away as Sweden, Japan, Australia, England and South Africa.\n*OSU is home to [[Fire Protection Publications]] and the [[International Fire Service Training Association]], the largest publisher of fire and emergency services books in North America.\n*OSU's Homecoming was awarded the Council for Advancement and Support of Education (CASE) Seal of Excellence. Presented each year by the Oklahoma State University Alumni Association, \"America's Greatest Homecoming Celebration\" began in 1913 and today draws more than 70,000 alumni and fans back to Stillwater for events like the Harvest Carnival, Walkaround and Sea of Orange Parade. It is widely regarded as one of the best homecoming celebrations in the U.S.<ref name=\"orangeconnection.org\"/>\n*Each year the School of Entrepreneurship hosts the \"Experiential Classroom\", an intensive 3-day seminar for entrepreneurship educators. It has been widely recognized as being the top program of its kind. In 2011, the program hosted entrepreneurship faculty from 29 states, 17 countries, and 65 different universities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spears.okstate.edu/news/2012/09/26/spears-school-hosts-entrepreneurship-faculty-from-29-states-17-countries-and-65-universities/|title=Spears School hosts entrepreneurship faculty from 29 states, 17 countries and 65 universities - Spears School of Business News|publisher=Spears.okstate.edu|accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Housing===\nCurrent university-owned housing options include 31 residence halls, more than 15 dining options, and six family-first apartment complexes. In recent years, on-campus housing has been undergoing significant transformation. Student living was previously dominated by traditional residence halls; however, apartment-style buildings now comprise approximately half of the living quarters.<ref name=\"reslife.okstate.edu\">https://reslife.okstate.edu/housing-options/neighborhoods/</ref> In 2005, the high-rise Willham North and South residence halls that once dominated the Stillwater skyline were demolished and replaced with the Village suites on its site.<ref>https://www.ocolly.com/suites-to-replace-willham-north-and-south/article_27d0ae48-28f1-555e-9f89-c0b562520044.html</ref> Iba Hall, another traditional hall, was closed in 2007, but was reopened in 2011 due to an increase of incoming freshman.<ref>https://www.ocolly.com/iba-hall-closing-after-summer/article_8bc479b0-904a-519d-aeca-d036d007a504.html</ref> In 2017, Iba Hall underwent significant renovations which lasted through most of that year, before reopening in time for the Fall 2018 semester.\n\nIba, Parker, Wentz and Stout Halls continue to offer traditional residence hall accommodations. In addition, three residence halls were opened in the fall of 2015, collectively known as the University Commons. North houses female students, south houses male students, and west is a co-ed facility that also houses the twenty-four-hour service desk for the area. Although Kerr-Drummond was slated to be closed with the opening of the University Commons, Drummond was reopened in fall 2015 due to increased occupancy of campus housing.<ref>https://www.ocolly.com/news/residential-life-announces-closure-of-drummond-hall/article_46b487d2-2703-11e8-9a05-57e2f67ae30e.html</ref> Kerr was closed and is scheduled for demolition in the coming years. Apartments for single students are Bost, Davis, Morsani-Smith, Peterson-Friend, Kamm, Sitlington and Young Halls. Housing in suite-style accommodations are provided in the named Village CASNR (College of Agricultural Science and Natural Resources), Village HS (Human Sciences), Village C, Village D, Village E and Village F. Deluxe suites are provided in Patchin & Jones, Bennett, Zink & Allen, and Stinchcomb & Booker Halls.<ref>https://reslife.okstate.edu/housing-options/halls/index.html</ref> Graduate students and families are offered accommodations in seven apartment \"neighborhoods\" with a variety of floor plans and amenities: Brumley, Demaree, Prosser, Stevens, West, and Williams.<ref name=\"reslife.okstate.edu\"/>\n\nAdditionally, a number of learning communities and special interest housing options are available, providing opportunity for students who share interests or majors to live together. Most of these communities occupy certain floors of buildings or halls, rather than consisting of separate buildings. Included among the options are: FIT (Freshman in Transition, College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources), athletic training, career exploration (College of Arts and Sciences), computer science floor, engineering floors, health and sciences floor, HS housing (College of Human and Environmental Sciences), journalism and broadcasting housing, Kamm Leadership House, Ketchum House (Native American interests), James Building (Young Engineers House), Maude's Quad (Women in Engineering House), Recovery House (students recovering from drug and/or alcohol dependence), Spanish House (language immersion), Spears School of Business House, Stout Honors housing (University's Honors Program), Uhuru House (African Centered Cultural House), Wellness House, and The Transfer Zone (transfer students).\n{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Fraternity & Sorority life===\nOklahoma State University's fraternities and sororities celebrated 100 years of existence at OSU in 2008.\n\nSocial fraternities and sororities at Oklahoma State are divided among four councils: Panhellenic, Interfraternity, National Pan-Hellenic and Multicultural.\n\nThirteen national Panhellenic sororities have chapters at OSU. They are: [[Alpha Chi Omega]], [[Alpha Delta Pi]], [[Alpha Omicron Pi]], [[Alpha Xi Delta]], [[Chi Omega]], [[Delta Delta Delta]], [[Gamma Phi Beta]], [[Kappa Alpha Theta]], [[Kappa Delta]], [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]], [[Phi Mu]], [[Pi Beta Phi]], and [[Zeta Tau Alpha]].\n\nTwenty-one fraternities make up the Interfraternity Council. Member fraternities include: [[Alpha Gamma Rho]], [[Alpha Sigma Phi]], [[Alpha Tau Omega]], [[Beta Theta Pi]], Beta Upsilon Chi, [[Delta Tau Delta]], [[FarmHouse]], [[Kappa Alpha Order]], [[Kappa Sigma]], [[Lambda Chi Alpha]], [[Phi Delta Theta]], [[Phi Gamma Delta]], Phi Kappa Sigma, [[Phi Kappa Tau]], [[Pi Kappa Alpha]], [[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]], [[Sigma Chi]], [[Sigma Nu]], [[Sigma Phi Epsilon]], [[Sigma Tau Gamma]], and [[Theta Chi]].\n\nNPHC member organizations are historically black fraternities and sororities. As of the 2018-2019 school year, [[Alpha Phi Alpha]], [[Delta Sigma Theta]], [[Omega Psi Phi]], [[Phi Beta Sigma]], and [[Zeta Phi Beta]] have chapters at OSU.\n\nThe Multicultural Greek Council is the umbrella organization for additional minority Greek letter groups. Member organizations include [[Alpha Pi Omega]], [[Kappa Delta Chi]], [[Sigma Lambda Alpha (sorority)|Sigma Lambda Alpha]], [[Sigma Lambda Beta]], [[Omega Delta Phi]].\n\n===Student organizations===\nOrganizations are available to students through the university that serve any interest. A complete list of campus organizations can be found on OSU's website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://campuslink.okstate.edu/organizations|title=Oklahoma State Student Organization List|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504011840/https://campuslink.okstate.edu/organizations|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=May 5, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Main|Oklahoma State Cowboys and Cowgirls}}\n[[File:Oklahoma State University Athletics logo.svg|thumb|OSU athletics logo]]\n[[File:2008 UH Cougars vs Oklahoma State Cowboys.jpg|thumb|Houston Cougars vs Oklahoma State Cowboys football game at [[:en:Boone Pickens Stadium|Boone Pickens Stadium]] in 2008]]\n'''Stats:'''\n:[[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] Division I-A\n:Conference: [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]]\n:Major Rivalries: [[Oklahoma Sooners|University of Oklahoma Sooners]]\n:Minor Rivalries: [[Texas Longhorns|University of Texas Longhorns]], [[University of Kansas Jayhawks]], [[Iowa State Cyclones wrestling|Iowa State University Cyclones]] (wrestling)\n::[[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] Championships: 52 (#4 after Stanford, USC, and UCLA)\n:: [[Oklahoma State Cowboys wrestling|Wrestling]]: 34\n:: [[Golf]]: 11\n:: [[Basketball]]: 2 (1945 and 1946)\n:: [[Baseball]]: 1 (1959)\n:: [[Cross country running|Cross Country]]: 4 (1954, 2009, 2010, 2012)\n\n::National Championships not sanctioned by NCAA: 5\n:: [[Equestrianism|Equestrian]]: 4\n:: [[College Football|Football]]: 1 (1945)\n:Athletic Director: [[Mike Holder]]\n\n===Football===\n{{Main|Oklahoma State Cowboys football}}\n10 conference titles \u2013 26 bowl games played \u2013 1988 Heisman Trophy winner and single season rushing record ([[Barry Sanders]]).\n\n===Basketball===\n{{Main|Oklahoma State Cowboys men's basketball|Oklahoma State Cowgirls basketball}}\nMen's basketball is tradition rich at Oklahoma State. Oklahoma State made the [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Championship|Final Four]] in 1995 and 2004 and was the first ever Division 1 basketball program to win back-to-back National Championships in 1945-1946.\n\n===Wrestling===\n{{Main|Oklahoma State Cowboys wrestling}}\nThe [[Oklahoma State Cowboys wrestling|Cowboy wrestling team]] brought home their 33rd [[NCAA Wrestling Team Championship|NCAA championship]] in spring 2005, scoring the most points ever by an Oklahoma State wrestling team in the NCAA. OSU won their 34th overall (and 4th consecutive) title in 2006.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.big12sports.com/sports/m-wrestl/spec-rel/031906aaa.html | title=Oklahoma State Wins Fourth Straight NCAA Wrestling Title | publisher=big12sports.com | accessdate=March 29, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061106171557/http://www.big12sports.com/sports/m-wrestl/spec-rel/031906aaa.html |archivedate = November 6, 2006}}</ref> OSU's 34 team titles are the most ever collected by a school in one sport. The Cowboys have also produced 127 individual national champions, including the sport's first-ever four-time champion, Pat Smith.\n\n===Other sports===\nSince the [[1924 Summer Olympics|1924 Olympics]], 68 [[List of Oklahoma State University Olympians|Oklahoma State University Olympians]] have won a total of 30 medals: 21 gold, four silver, and five bronze.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://okstate.com/sports/2015/3/17/GEN_2014010165.aspx|title=Olympians|website=okstate.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==Fight songs==\nNotable among a number of songs commonly played and sung at various events such as [[Graduation|commencement]], [[convocation]], and athletic games are: ''The Waving Song'', ''Ride 'Em Cowboys'' (the Oklahoma State University [[fight song]]), and the ''OSU Chant''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://okstate.com/sports/2015/3/17/GEN_201401011.aspx|title=Oklahoma State University Gameday Traditions|website=okstate.com}}</ref> At the end of every sporting event, win or lose, OSU student-athletes face the [[student section]] and sing the [[alma mater]] along with other students, faculty, alumni and staff.\n\n==People==\n{{Main|List of Oklahoma State University people}}\n\nToday, there are more than 200,000 living OSU alumni worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orangeconnection.org/s/860/index-blue.aspx?sid=860&gid=1&pgid=377 |title=OSU Alumni Association |publisher=Orangeconnection.org |accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> Prominent alumni include oil tycoon and billionaire philanthropist [[T. Boone Pickens]], actor [[James Marsden]], \"the father of the personal computer\" [[Ed Roberts (computer engineer)|Ed Roberts]], country singers [[Garth Brooks]] and [[Hoyt Axton]], former Prime Minister of South Korea [[Nam Duck-woo]], former Prime Minister of Jordan [[Adnan Badran]], US Senator [[Tom Coburn]], former [[Governor of Oklahoma]] [[Mary Fallin]],  former acting [[Surgeon General of the United States]] [[Robert A. Whitney]], Oklahoma Supreme Court Justice [[Steven W. Taylor]], [[David Noel Ram\u00edrez Padilla]] rector of [[Tecnol\u00f3gico de Monterrey]] Mexico's most prestigious university, former [[Central Bank of Somalia]] Governor [[Yussur A.F. Abrar]], production designer and drummer [[K.K. Barrett]], legal scholar [[Anita Hill]], and [[Ponnala Lakshmaiah]], an Indian politician.\n\nInterviews with OSU Alumni can be viewed and heard through the O-State Stories Project of the Oklahoma Oral History Research Program.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.library.okstate.edu/oralhistory/ostate/index.htm |title=O-State Stories Oral History Project, Oklahoma Oral History Research Program |publisher=Library.okstate.edu |date=December 8, 2010 |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110409005048/http://www.library.okstate.edu/oralhistory/ostate/index.htm |archivedate=April 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty===\nA number of prominent scholars, authors and researchers have served on the OSU faculty, including poet [[Ai (poet)|Ai]], historian [[Angie Debo]], literary critic and author [[Brian Evenson]], mathematician [[William Jaco]], computer scientist and philosopher [[Subhash Kak]], chemical engineering scholar [[Nicholas A. Kotov]],  information studies pioneer and research librarian [[Edmon Low]], engineering pioneer [[J. Tinsley Oden]], and highly cited psychologist [[Robert Sternberg]] (who now teaches at [[Cornell University]]).\n\nIn recent decades, number of notable academic administrators have served on the Oklahoma State faculty, including [[Guy Bailey]] (who would serve as President of the [[University of Alabama]]), [[Ray M. Bowen]] (who served as President of [[Texas A&M]]), Hilton Briggs (who served as President of [[South Dakota State University]]), [[Robert W. MacVicar]] (who went on to become President of [[Oregon State University]]), [[James E. Martin]] (who served as President at Auburn and the [[University of Arkansas]]), [[J. Tinsley Oden]] (who served as Provost for the [[University of Texas at Austin]]), [[Robert Sternberg]] (who left to become President of the [[University of Wyoming]]), and [[Paul Torgersen]] (who served as President of [[Virginia Tech]]).\n\n===Athletics===\nCoaching alumni include OSU wrestling head coach [[John Smith (wrestler)|John Smith]], OSU football head coach [[Mike Gundy]], and former OSU basketball coaches [[Eddie Sutton]] and [[Sean Sutton]]. The Cowboys have produced several NBA players, including [[Desmond Mason]], formerly of the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]], [[Marcus Smart]] of the [[Boston Celtics]], [[Jawun Evans]] of the [[Los Angeles Clippers]], [[Tony Allen (basketball)|Tony Allen]] of the [[New Orleans Pelicans]], [[James Anderson (basketball)|James Anderson]] of the [[Sacramento Kings]], [[Joey Graham]] of the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]], [[Stephen Graham (basketball)|Stephen Graham]] of the [[New Jersey Nets]], [[JamesOn Curry]] of the [[Chicago Bulls]], [[Terrel Harris]] of the [[Miami Heat]], and former [[New York Knicks]] guard [[John Starks (basketball)|John Starks]]. [[NFL]] players [[Barry Sanders]] and [[Thurman Thomas]] also attended OSU, as did baseball All-Star pitcher [[Joe Horlen]] and All-Star third baseman [[Robin Ventura]]. Ventura went on to manage the Chicago White Sox for five seasons. Also in the [[NFL]] are former Cowboys [[Dez Bryant]] and [[Dan Bailey (American football)|Dan Bailey]] of the [[Dallas Cowboys]], and [[Kevin Williams (defensive tackle)|Kevin Williams]] of the [[Minnesota Vikings]]. Retired MMA and UFC Hall of Famers [[Randy Couture]] and [[Don Frye]], and former [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] welterweight champion [[Johny Hendricks]] wrestled at OSU. Former [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] light heavyweight champion [[Daniel Cormier]] wrestled at the university, as well as other MMA fighters including [[Mark Munoz]]. PGA professional golfers [[Rickie Fowler]], [[Scott Verplank]], [[Bo Van Pelt]], [[Charles Howell III]], [[Bob Tway]], and [[Hunter Mahan]] also attended OSU. Two-time gold medalist, ESPN analyst,  and ASA Hall of Fame inductee [[Michele Mary Smith]] played softball at OSU. [[Houston Nutt]] and [[Brent Guy]], both former players and teammates, became head coaches after serving as assistants for the Cowboy football program.\n\n==Campus buildings==\n:''Listed below are just a few of the buildings at OSU. For a complete list, visit [[List of Oklahoma State University buildings]].''\n\n===Academic buildings===\n<!-- KEEP THIS LIST IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n[[File:OSUEdmonLowLibrary2007.jpg|thumb|Edmon Low Library]]\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* 4-H Youth Development\n* Advanced Technology Research Center\n* Agriculture\n* Agriculture North\n* Animal Sciences\n* Bartlett Center for the Visual Arts\n* Biosystems and Agriculture Engineering Lab\n* Classroom Building\n* [[Colvin Center]]\n* Donald W. Reynolds School of Architecture\n* [[Edmon Low Library]]\n* Endeavor Lab\n* Engineering North\n* Engineering South\n* General Academic Building (former Spears School of Business)\n* Gundersen\n* Henry Bellmon Research Center\n* Human Sciences\n* Human Sciences West\n* Life Sciences East\n* Life Sciences West\n* Mathematical Sciences\n* McElroy Hall\n* [[Morrill Hall (Oklahoma State University)|Morrill Hall]]\n* Murray Hall\n* Noble Research Center\n* North Classroom\n* North Murray\n* [[Old Central]] \n* Paul Miller Journalism and Broadcasting Center\n* Physical Sciences\n* Robert M. Kerr Food & Agricultural Products\n* Seretean Center for the Performing Arts\n* Spears School of Business\n* [[Whitehurst Hall]]\n* Willard Hall\n* Wes Watkins Center for International Trade Development\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Residential buildings===\n[[File:Kerr-Drummond Hall.jpg|thumb|Kerr and Drummond halls]]\n<!-- KEEP THIS LIST IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Allen Hall\n* Cordell Hall (now closed)\n* Davis Hall\n* Drummond Hall (now closed)\n* Kerr Hall (now closed)\n* Morsani-Smith\n* Parker Hall\n* Wentz Hall\n* Patchin Hall\n* Jones Hall\n* Booker Hall\n* Stinchcomb Hall\n* Iba Hall\n* Bennett Hall\n* Stout Hall\n* University Commons\n* University Village Suites\n* Willham North Hall (now closed)\n* Willham South Hall (now closed)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Other buildings===\n[[File:Gallagher-Iba Arena, Stillwater, Oklahoma.jpg|thumb|Historic Gallagher-Iba Arena and the OSU Spirit Rider statue]]\n<!-- KEEP THIS LIST IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n* Allie P. Reynolds Stadium \u2013 Baseball\n* [[Bennett Memorial Chapel]]\n* [[Boone Pickens Stadium]] \u2013 Football stadium named after [[T. Boone Pickens]]\n* [[Cowgirl Stadium]]\n* Historic [[Gallagher-Iba Arena]] \u2013 Named top collegiate venue in the United States by [[CBS]] Sportsline. It is named after [[Edward C. Gallagher (wrestling)|Edward C. Gallagher]] and [[Henry Iba]]. It is home to practice facilities, weight and locker rooms as well as the original white maple wood basketball court. The court is named [[Eddie Sutton]] Court, in honor of the former OSU Men's Basketball Coach. Sutton led the Cowboys to two Final Four appearances during his time as coach.\n* [[National Wrestling Hall of Fame and Museum]]\n* [[Student Union (Oklahoma State University)|Student Union]] \u2013 Known as the largest [[Student activity center|student union]] in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://union.okstate.edu/about_union.htm |title=About Us |publisher=Union.okstate.edu |date=August 20, 1950 |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717041139/http://union.okstate.edu/about_union.htm |archivedate=July 17, 2011 }}</ref> Portions of the 1992 film ''[[All-American Murder]]'' were filmed at the Student Union.<ref>{{cite web | title=Filming Locations for All-American Murder (1992) (V) | publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]\n|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0103652/locations | accessdate=January 28, 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Whitehurst Hall]] administration building\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Oklahoma}}\n* [[Gift of a Lifetime]]\n* [[Johnny Bright Incident]] \u2013 An incident that occurred during a football game on Saturday, October 20, 1951\n* [[List of forestry universities and colleges]]\n{{Clear}}\n*[[Oklahoma Agricultural Experiment Station]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Oklahoma State University}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.okstate.com/ Oklahoma State Athletics website]\n* {{Cite Collier's|wstitle=Oklahoma Agricultural and Mechanical College |short=x}}\n\n{{Oklahoma State University|campus}}\n{{Big 12 Conference navbox}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Oklahoma}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oklahoma State University-Stillwater}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Stillwater, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Education in Payne County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1890]]\n[[Category:Land-grant universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma State University| ]]\n[[Category:Veterinary schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Stillwater, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:1890 establishments in Oklahoma Territory]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Oklahoma State University|other system schools|Oklahoma State University System}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Oklahoma State University\u2013Stillwater\n| image_name = Oklahoma State University seal.svg\n| image_upright = 0.7\n| established = {{start date|1890|12|25}}\n| type =[[Flagship university|Flagship]]<br />[[Public university|Public]]<br />[[Land-grant university|Land-grant]]<br />[[Space-grant university|Space-grant]] \n| affiliation = Oklahoma Agricultural & Mechanical Colleges\n| academic_affiliation= {{unbulleted list|[[Oklahoma State University System|OSU System]]|[[Association of Public and Land-Grant Universities|APLU]]|[[Oak Ridge Associated Universities|ORAU]]}}\n| endowment = $756.5 million (2019)<ref>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2019-Endowment-Market-Values--Final-Feb-10.ashx? |title=U.S. and Canadian 2019 NTSE Participating Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2019 Endowment Market Value, and Percentage Change in Market Value from FY18 to FY19 (Revised) |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| city = [[Stillwater, Oklahoma|Stillwater]]\n| state = [[Oklahoma]]\n| country = United States\n| coor = {{coord|36|07|56|N|97|04|51|W|type:edu_region:US-OK|display=inline,title}}\n| president = [[V. Burns Hargis]]\n| enrollment = 25,295<ref name=\"Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education\">{{cite web |url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=207388 |title=Oklahoma State University - Main Campus |publisher=Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education |date=2017 |accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| staff = 1,857\n| campus = [[City|Small city]], {{convert|1489|acre|km2}} on the Stillwater campus<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vpaf.okstate.edu/bam/Space/History.htm |title=History and Background Information \u2013 Budget & Asset Management \u2013 Oklahoma State University |publisher=Vpaf.okstate.edu |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720020634/http://vpaf.okstate.edu/bam/Space/History.htm |archivedate=July 20, 2011}}</ref>\n| colors = Orange and Black<ref>{{cite web|title=Oklahoma State University's Official Colors|url=https://brand.okstate.edu/site-files/documents/osu_colors.jpg|date=July 1, 2019 |accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref><br />{{college color boxes|Oklahoma State Cowboys}}\n| nickname = [[Oklahoma State Cowboys and Cowgirls|Cowboys and Cowgirls]]\n| sporting_affiliations = [[NCAA Division I]] \u2013 [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]]\n| mascot = [[Pistol Pete (Oklahoma State University)|Pistol Pete]]\n| website = {{url|go.okstate.edu}}\n| logo = Oklahoma State University system logo.svg\n| logo_upright = .7\n}}\n\n'''Oklahoma State University''' ('''OSU''') is a [[Public university|public]] [[land-grant university|land-grant]] [[research university]] in [[Stillwater, Oklahoma]]. OSU was founded in 1890 under the [[Morrill Act]]. Originally known as '''Oklahoma Agricultural and Mechanical College''' ('''Oklahoma A&M'''), it is the flagship institution of the [[Oklahoma State University System]]. Official enrollment for the fall 2010 semester system-wide was 35,073, with 23,459<ref name=\"newsok.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2014_Endowment_Market_Values_Revised.pdf |title=2014 Endowment Market Value |publisher=nacubo.org |date=June 30, 2014 |accessdate=March 18, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223091003/http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2014_Endowment_Market_Values_Revised.pdf |archive-date=February 23, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> students enrolled at OSU-Stillwater. Enrollment shows the Freshman class of 2012 was the largest on record with 4,298 students.<ref name=\"newsok.com\"/> OSU is classified by the [[Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching|Carnegie Foundation]] as a research university with highest research activity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=207388 |title=Carnegie Foundation \u2013 Oklahoma State University \u2013 Main Campus |publisher=Carnegiefoundation.org |year=2010 |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Oklahoma State Cowboys and Cowgirls]]' athletic heritage includes 52 national championships, a total greater than all but three [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] schools in the United States, and first in the [[Big 12 Conference]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/champs_records_book/summaries/Men.pdf |title=NCAA Summary, National Collegiate/Division I Men's |format=PDF |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627170857/http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/champs_records_book/summaries/Men.pdf |archivedate=June 27, 2010 }}</ref>  Students spend part of the fall semester preparing for OSU's Homecoming celebration, begun in 1913, which draws more than 40,000 alumni and over 70,000 participants each year to campus and is billed by the university as \"America's Greatest Homecoming Celebration.\"<ref name=\"orangeconnection.org\">{{cite web|url=http://orangeconnection.org/s/860/homecoming-interior.aspx?sid=860&gid=1&pgid=3768 |title=OSU Alumni Association \u2013 Homecoming History |publisher=Orangeconnection.org |date=October 30, 1920 |accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Old Central.jpg|thumb|left|[[Old Central]] at Oklahoma A&M, 1894]]\n[[File:Williams-Hall-Library-OKStateU-formerlyAM-Stillwater.jpg|thumb|Williams Hall, the Castle of the Prairies, in 1920]]\nOn December 25, 1890, the [[Oklahoma territory|Oklahoma Territorial]] Legislature finally gained approval for '''Oklahoma Territorial Agricultural and Mechanical (A&M) College''', the [[land-grant]] university established under the Morrill Act of 1862. It specified that the college was to be within [[Payne County, Oklahoma|Payne County]]. Such an ambiguous description created rivalry between towns within the county, with Stillwater ultimately winning out. Upon statehood in 1907, \"Territorial\" was dropped from its title.\n[[File:OklahomaA&MSeal.png|thumb|left|Oklahoma A&M seal]]\nThe first students assembled for class on December 14, 1891. Classes were held for two and one-half years in local churches until the first academic building, later known as [[Old Central]], was dedicated on June 15, 1894, on the southeast corner of campus, which at the time was flat plowed prairie.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.library.okstate.edu/scua/exhibit/campusbeg/index.htm |title=Campus Beginnings: 1890\u20131940 \u2013 SCUA Online Exhibit \u2013 OSU Library |publisher=Library.okstate.edu |date=January 29, 2007 |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101230515/http://www.library.okstate.edu/scua/exhibit/campusbeg/index.htm |archivedate=January 1, 2011}}</ref> In 1896, '''Oklahoma A&M''' held its first commencement with six male graduates. The first Library was established in Old Central in one room shared with the English Department.  The first campus building to have electricity, Williams Hall, was constructed in 1900. With its turreted architecture it was referred to as the \"Castle of the Prairies\";<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.library.okstate.edu/about/history.htm |title=OSU Library History |publisher=Library.okstate.edu |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324062655/http://www.library.okstate.edu/about/history.htm |archive-date=March 24, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> It remained standing until 1969. One of the earliest campus buildings was also a barn, used as part of an agricultural experiment station, which was served by a large reservoir pond created in 1895.  The barn burned in 1922, but the pond, enlarged and remodeled in 1928 and 1943, is now known as Theta Pond, a popular campus scenic landmark.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.library.okstate.edu/scua/exhibit/theta/index.htm |title=Special Collections: Theta Pond |publisher=Library.okstate.edu |date=September 22, 2008 |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110102101236/http://www.library.okstate.edu/scua/exhibit/theta/index.htm |archivedate=January 2, 2011}}</ref> In 1906, Morrill Hall was completed and became the principal building on campus. A fire gutted the building in 1914, but the outside structure survived intact, and the interior was reconstructed.\n\n[[File:Oklahoma A&M Boys Dormitory.jpg|thumb|left|Boy's Dormitory, later Crutchfield Hall]]\nOn-campus housing at Oklahoma A&M College began in 1910, with the opening of the Boy's Dormitory.<ref name=dorm>{{cite web|title=OSU Housing and Residential Life celebrates centennial|date=October 18, 2010|publisher=Oklahoma State Housing and Residential Life|url=https://news.okstate.edu/articles/communications/2010/osu-housing-and-residential-life-celebrates-centennial.html|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref> Later renamed Crutchfield Hall, the [[Historic American Buildings Survey]] said it was significant as \"... the first permanent boy's dormitory in Oklahoma ... [and] the sole surviving example of a pre-1930 utilitarian dormitory that is characteristic of modified Italian Renaissance Revival architecture\".<ref>{{cite web|title=\nOklahoma State University, Boys Dormitory, Northwest corner of Hester Street & Athletic Avenue, Stillwater, Payne County, OK|publisher=[[Historic American Buildings Survey]]|url=https://www.loc.gov/pictures/collection/hh/item/ok0069/|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref> Crutchfield Hall later served the School of Music and the College of Engineering, Architecture, and Technology before its demolition in 1955.<ref name=dorm /> Also opened in 1910 was the Women's Building, containing a dining hall, home economics classes, and a women's gymnasium, in addition to resident housing for female students. It was later named Garner Hall and survives to the present day as the Bartlett Center for the Studio Arts and houses the Gardiner Art Gallery.<ref name=dorm /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://art.okstate.edu/facilities/gardiner.php |title=Facilities // Oklahoma State University Department of Art |publisher=Art.okstate.edu |accessdate=October 26, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504150420/http://art.okstate.edu/facilities/gardiner.php |archivedate=May 4, 2015}}</ref> By 1919 the campus included Morrill Hall, the Central Building, the Engineering Building (now [[Gundersen Hall]]), the Women's building, the Auditorium (replaced later by the Seretean Center for Performing Arts),<ref>[http://music.okstate.edu/sereteancenter.php] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604122454/http://music.okstate.edu/sereteancenter.php|date=June 4, 2010}}</ref> the Armory-Gymnasium (now the Architecture Building) and the Power Plant.<ref>[A History of the Oklahoma State University Campus, by J. Lewie Sanderson, R. Dean McGlamery, and David C. Peters]</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of [[World War II]], Oklahoma A&M was one of six schools selected by the [[United States Navy]] to give the Primary School in the [[Electronics Training Program]] (ETP), also known as Naval Training School Elementary Electricity and Radio Materiel (NTS EE&RM).<ref>[http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/ref/USN-Act/OK.html%20US%20Naval%20Activities%20WWII%20By%20State]{{dead link|date=October 2015}}</ref> Starting in March 1942, each month a new group of 100 Navy students arrived for three months of 14-hour days in concentrated electrical engineering study. Cordell Hall, the newest dormitory, was used for housing and meals; lectures and lab sessions were held in the Engineering Building. Professor Emory B. Phillips was the Director of Instruction. ETP admission required passing the [[Eddy Test]], one of the most selective qualifying exams given during the war years.<ref>Test and Research Staff, Bureau of Naval Personnel; \u201cPsychological test construction and research in the Bureau of Naval Personnel. Part V. Navy radio technician training program\u201d; ''American Psychologist'', vol 1(3), Mar. 1946, pp 80-90</ref> At a given time, some 500 Navy students were on the campus, a significant fraction of the war-years enrollment. The training activity continued until June 1945, and served a total of about 7,000 students; among these was [[Robert B. Kamm]], a future professor and president of Oklahoma State University.<ref>Naeter, Albrecht; \"Naval Training School,\" ''The Oklahoma State Engineer'', Dec. 1943</ref><ref>Watson, Raymond C., Jr.; ''Solving the Naval Radar Crisis'', Trafford Publishing, 2007, pp. 208-211, {{ISBN|978-1-4251-6173-6}}</ref> During some of the war years, the Navy also had a [[Yeoman (US Navy)|Yeoman]] training activity for [[WAVES]] and [[SPARS]] on the campus.\n[[File:Student Union - Oklahoma State University.jpg|thumb|Student Union Building at OSU]]\nMuch of the growth of Oklahoma A&M and the campus architectural integrity can be attributed to work of [[Henry G. Bennett]], who served as the school's president from 1928 to 1950. Early in his tenure Dr. Bennett developed a strategic vision for the physical expansion of the university campus. The plan was adopted in 1937 and his vision was followed for more than fifty years, making the university what it is today, including the [[Georgian architecture]] that permeates the campus. The focal point of his vision was a centrally located library building, which became a reality when the [[Edmon Low Library]] opened in 1953. Another major addition to the campus during the Bennett years was the construction of the Student Union, which opened in 1950. Subsequent additions and renovations have made the building one of the largest student union buildings in the world at {{convert|611000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://union.okstate.edu/renovation/BuildingHistory.htm |title=OSU Student Union Building History |publisher=Union.okstate.edu |date=September 9, 1950 |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720020635/http://union.okstate.edu/renovation/BuildingHistory.htm |archivedate=July 20, 2011}}</ref> A complete renovation and further expansion of the building began in 2010.\n\n[[File:HenryBennettStatueatOSU.jpg|thumb|left|Statue of Henry G. Bennett near Library Lawn at OSU]]\nOn May 15, 1957, '''Oklahoma A&M''' changed its name '''Oklahoma State University of Agricultural and Applied Sciences''' to reflect the broadening scope of curriculum offered. Oklahoma Gov. [[Raymond Gary]] signed the bill authorizing the name change passed by the 26th Oklahoma Legislature on May 15, 1957. However, the bill only authorized the Board of Regents to change the name of the college, a measure they voted on at their meeting on June 6. However, the name was quickly shortened to '''Oklahoma State University''' for most purposes, and the \"Agricultural & Applied Sciences\" name was formally dropped in 1980. Subsequently, the [[Oklahoma State University System]] was created, with the Stillwater campus as the flagship institution and several outlying branches: [[Oklahoma State University - Okmulgee|OSU-Institute of Technology]] in [[Okmulgee, OK|Okmulgee]] (1946), [[Oklahoma State University - Oklahoma City|OSU-Oklahoma City]] (1961), [[Oklahoma State University - Tulsa|OSU-Tulsa]] (1984), and the [[Oklahoma State University - Center for Health Sciences|Center for Health Sciences]] also in [[Tulsa]] (1988).<ref>[http://osu.okstate.edu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=280&Itemid=96 \"OSU History\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901073919/http://osu.okstate.edu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=280&Itemid=96 |date=September 1, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, OSU announced its \"Campus Master Plan\", a campaign to enhance academic, athletic, and administrative facilities. Over $800 million is ear-marked for campus construction and renovation over twenty years. The Plan calls for an \"athletic village\" where all of the university's athletic facilities will be located on the main campus. To accomplish this goal, the athletic department bought all (or nearly all) the property north of [[Boone Pickens Stadium]] up to McElroy between Knoblock and Washington streets. This drew criticism from the city of Stillwater and property owners.<ref>{{cite web | title=Pickens's Donation to Oklahoma State Spurs Fight on Land Grab | work=Boone State | url=http://clerestoryav.com/boonestate/bloomberg.html | accessdate=May 24, 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008110609/http://clerestoryav.com/boonestate/bloomberg.html | archivedate=October 8, 2007 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>  While the vast majority of the real estate was rental property targeting college students, a few owners were longtime residents. There was a lone holdout in this parcel of land, who sued OSU over their right to use [[eminent domain]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Lone Holdout Blocks Pickens's Vast Sports Project at Oklahoma State U. | work=The Chronicle of Higher Education | url=http://chronicle.com/news/article/1063/lone-holdout-blocks-pickenss-vast-sports-project-at-oklahoma-state-u| accessdate=May 24, 2007}}</ref> The case was decided in favor of the University. The project includes the construction of an indoor practice facility for most sports, a soccer stadium/outdoor track, a tennis complex, and a baseball stadium.\n[[File:Edmon Low Library - Oklahoma State University.jpg|thumb|right|Edmon Low Library]]\nIn 2006, OSU became the recipient of a gift of $165 million from alumnus [[T. Boone Pickens]] to the university's athletic department, and in 2008 received another gift from Pickens of $100 million for endowed academic chairs.  It was the largest gift for academics ever given in the state.<ref>[http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/052208dnmetpickens.152d3ba1.html Dallas Morning News, \"T. Boone Pickens donates $100M to OSU\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907043832/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/052208dnmetpickens.152d3ba1.html |date=September 7, 2008 }}</ref>  Ethical concerns have been raised in media reports about the propriety of how some of the Pickens gifts have been made, immediately returned to Pickens, and then placed in hedge funds owned by Pickens' companies<ref>{{cite news|last=Gose|first=Ben|title=Concerns are Raised about how Oklahoma State U Handled a Gift |url=http://chronicle.com/article/Concerns-Are-Raised-About-How/1287/|newspaper=Chronicle of Higher Education|date=October 30, 2008}}</ref>  In February 2010, Pickens announced that he was pledging another $100 million to fund a scholarship endowment as part of a $1 billion fund-raising campaign titled \"Branding Success.\" The pledge brought the total pledged or contributed to OSU by Pickens to over $500 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/with-t.-boone-pickens-gift-osu-kicks-off-drive-for-1b/article/3442701 |title=NewsOK, \"With T. Boone Pickens\u2019 gift, OSU kicks off drive for $1B\" |publisher=Newsok.com |date=February 27, 2010 |accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 2015 during the annual homecoming parade, Adacia Chambers [[2015 Oklahoma State University homecoming parade crash|drove her vehicle into a crowd of people]] killing 4 people and injuring 47.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/woman-faces-2nd-degree-murder-charges-in-oklahoma-crash/ar-BBmoHa8?li=AAa0dzB&ocid=mailsignout|title=Woman faces 2nd-degree murder charges in Oklahoma crash|publisher=Msn.com|accessdate=October 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029003114/http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/woman-faces-2nd-degree-murder-charges-in-oklahoma-crash/ar-BBmoHa8?li=AAa0dzB&ocid=mailsignout|archive-date=October 29, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Colleges ==\nOklahoma State University\u2013Stillwater offers nearly 200 undergraduate degree majors through six Colleges:\n* Ferguson College of Agriculture (Previously the College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources)\n* College of Arts and Sciences\n* College of Education, Health, and Aviation\n* College of Engineering, Architecture, and Technology\n* College of Human Sciences\n* Spears School of Business\n\nOSU provides further opportunities for select students to study, conduct research, and exchange ideas in a more challenging and supportive academic environment through the Honors College.\n\nThe graduate degree programs of all colleges are administered through the Graduate College.\n\nThe Center for Veterinary Health Sciences (CVHS) has three academic Departments: Veterinary Pathobiology, Physiological Sciences, and Veterinary Clinical Sciences. Each of the three academic departments share responsibility for the four-year professional curriculum leading to the [[Doctor of Veterinary Medicine]] (D.V.M.) degree. The interdepartmental Veterinary Biomedical Sciences graduate program offers MS and PhD degrees. It also offers ECFVG and PAVE programmes for foreign trained veterinarians.\n\n==Rankings and reputation==\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| ARWU_W = 501\u2013600\n| ARWU_N = 138\u2013155\n| THE_WSJ = 373\n| Forbes = 358\n| QS_W = 751\u2013800\n| THES_W = 401\u2013500\n| USNWR_W = 493\n| USNWR_NU = 192\n| Wamo_NU = 153\n}}\nAs a land-grant university, OSU has several historically renowned programs, including the College of [[Agricultural]] Sciences and Natural Resources and the College of [[Veterinary Medicine]]. The College of Engineering is renowned in the fields of architecture and mechanical engineering. The School of Entrepreneurship is internationally renowned at both the practical and academic levels.\n*It has been named a ''Truman Honor Institution'' for its success in producing [[Harry S. Truman Scholarship|Truman scholars]].<ref>[http://okcbusiness.com/business_people_view.asp?pID=876 OKCBusiness \u2013 Oklahoma City Business News] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403121550/http://okcbusiness.com/business_people_view.asp?pID=876 |date=April 3, 2008 }}</ref>\n*OSU is one of five U.S. universities where [[Sun Grant Research Initiative]] programs have been established by the U.S. Congress in the Sun Grant Research Initiative Act of 2003 for the purposes of researching and developing sustainable and environmentally-friendly bio-based energy alternatives.\n*The Math Department has been recognized by the American Mathematics Association as one of four innovative programs in the nation and has produced four [[Sloan Fellowship]] winners.<ref>https://sloan.org/past-fellows</ref>\n*The [[Oklahoma Mesonet]], a state-of-the-art network of [[Biosphere|environmental monitoring]] stations that is an [[University of Oklahoma|OU]]-OSU partnership, won a special award from the [[American Meteorological Society]] (AMS), the nation's leading professional society for those in the atmospheric and related sciences at the [[National Weather Center]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mesonet.org/index.php/okfirst/program_history | title=Program Timeline | publisher=mesonet.org | accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref>\n*OSU is headquarters for the [[International Ground Source Heat Pump Association]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.igshpa.okstate.edu/about/about_us.htm |title=What is IGSHPA? |publisher=Igshpa.okstate.edu |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404051034/http://www.igshpa.okstate.edu/about/about_us.htm |archive-date=April 4, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which has members from as far away as Sweden, Japan, Australia, England and South Africa.\n*OSU is home to [[Fire Protection Publications]] and the [[International Fire Service Training Association]], the largest publisher of fire and emergency services books in North America.\n*OSU's Homecoming was awarded the Council for Advancement and Support of Education (CASE) Seal of Excellence. Presented each year by the Oklahoma State University Alumni Association, \"America's Greatest Homecoming Celebration\" began in 1913 and today draws more than 70,000 alumni and fans back to Stillwater for events like the Harvest Carnival, Walkaround and Sea of Orange Parade. It is widely regarded as one of the best homecoming celebrations in the U.S.<ref name=\"orangeconnection.org\"/>\n*Each year the School of Entrepreneurship hosts the \"Experiential Classroom\", an intensive 3-day seminar for entrepreneurship educators. It has been widely recognized as being the top program of its kind. In 2011, the program hosted entrepreneurship faculty from 29 states, 17 countries, and 65 different universities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spears.okstate.edu/news/2012/09/26/spears-school-hosts-entrepreneurship-faculty-from-29-states-17-countries-and-65-universities/|title=Spears School hosts entrepreneurship faculty from 29 states, 17 countries and 65 universities - Spears School of Business News|publisher=Spears.okstate.edu|accessdate=October 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Housing===\nCurrent university-owned housing options include 31 residence halls, more than 15 dining options, and six family-first apartment complexes. In recent years, on-campus housing has been undergoing significant transformation. Student living was previously dominated by traditional residence halls; however, apartment-style buildings now comprise approximately half of the living quarters.<ref>https://reslife.okstate.edu/housing-options/neighborhoods/</ref> In 2005, the high-rise Willham North and South residence halls that once dominated the Stillwater skyline were demolished and replaced with the Village suites on its site.<ref>https://www.ocolly.com/suites-to-replace-willham-north-and-south/article_27d0ae48-28f1-555e-9f89-c0b562520044.html</ref> Iba Hall, another traditional hall, was closed in 2007, but was reopened in 2011 due to an increase of incoming freshman.<ref>https://www.ocolly.com/iba-hall-closing-after-summer/article_8bc479b0-904a-519d-aeca-d036d007a504.html</ref> In 2017, Iba Hall underwent significant renovations which lasted through most of that year, before reopening in time for the Fall 2018 semester.\n\nIba, Parker, Wentz and Stout Halls continue to offer traditional residence hall accommodations. In addition, three residence halls were opened in the fall of 2015, collectively known as the University Commons. North houses female students, south houses male students, and west is a co-ed facility that also houses the twenty-four-hour service desk for the area. Although Kerr-Drummond was slated to be closed with the opening of the University Commons, Drummond was reopened in fall 2015 due to increased occupancy of campus housing.<ref>https://www.ocolly.com/news/residential-life-announces-closure-of-drummond-hall/article_46b487d2-2703-11e8-9a05-57e2f67ae30e.html</ref> Kerr was closed and is scheduled for demolition in the coming years. Apartments for single students are Bost, Davis, Morsani-Smith, Peterson-Friend, Kamm, Sitlington and Young Halls. Housing in suite-style accommodations are provided in the named Village CASNR (College of Agricultural Science and Natural Resources), Village HS (Human Sciences), Village C, Village D, Village E and Village F. Deluxe suites are provided in Patchin & Jones, Bennett, Zink & Allen, and Stinchcomb & Booker Halls.<ref>https://reslife.okstate.edu/housing-options/halls/index.html</ref> Graduate students and families are offered accommodations in seven apartment \"neighborhoods\" with a variety of floor plans and amenities: Brumley, Demaree, Prosser, Stevens, West, and Williams.<ref>https://reslife.okstate.edu/housing-options/neighborhoods/</ref>\n\nAdditionally, a number of learning communities and special interest housing options are available, providing opportunity for students who share interests or majors to live together. Most of these communities occupy certain floors of buildings or halls, rather than consisting of separate buildings. Included among the options are: FIT (Freshman in Transition, College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources), athletic training, career exploration (College of Arts and Sciences), computer science floor, engineering floors, health and sciences floor, HS housing (College of Human and Environmental Sciences), journalism and broadcasting housing, Kamm Leadership House, Ketchum House (Native American interests), James Building (Young Engineers House), Maude's Quad (Women in Engineering House), Recovery House (students recovering from drug and/or alcohol dependence), Spanish House (language immersion), Spears School of Business House, Stout Honors housing (University's Honors Program), Uhuru House (African Centered Cultural House), Wellness House, and The Transfer Zone (transfer students).\n{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Fraternity & Sorority life===\nOklahoma State University's fraternities and sororities celebrated 100 years of existence at OSU in 2008.\n\nSocial fraternities and sororities at Oklahoma State are divided among four councils: Panhellenic, Interfraternity, National Pan-Hellenic and Multicultural.\n\nThirteen national Panhellenic sororities have chapters at OSU. They are: [[Alpha Chi Omega]], [[Alpha Delta Pi]], [[Alpha Omicron Pi]], [[Alpha Xi Delta]], [[Chi Omega]], [[Delta Delta Delta]], [[Gamma Phi Beta]], [[Kappa Alpha Theta]], [[Kappa Delta]], [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]], [[Phi Mu]], [[Pi Beta Phi]], and [[Zeta Tau Alpha]].\n\nTwenty-one fraternities make up the Interfraternity Council. Member fraternities include: [[Alpha Gamma Rho]], [[Alpha Sigma Phi]], [[Alpha Tau Omega]], [[Beta Theta Pi]], Beta Upsilon Chi, [[Delta Tau Delta]], [[FarmHouse]], [[Kappa Alpha Order]], [[Kappa Sigma]], [[Lambda Chi Alpha]], [[Phi Delta Theta]], [[Phi Gamma Delta]], Phi Kappa Sigma, [[Phi Kappa Tau]], [[Pi Kappa Alpha]], [[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]], [[Sigma Chi]], [[Sigma Nu]], [[Sigma Phi Epsilon]], [[Sigma Tau Gamma]], and [[Theta Chi]].\n\nNPHC member organizations are historically black fraternities and sororities. As of the 2018-2019 school year, [[Alpha Phi Alpha]], [[Delta Sigma Theta]], [[Omega Psi Phi]], [[Phi Beta Sigma]], and [[Zeta Phi Beta]] have chapters at OSU.\n\nThe Multicultural Greek Council is the umbrella organization for additional minority Greek letter groups. Member organizations include [[Alpha Pi Omega]], [[Kappa Delta Chi]], [[Sigma Lambda Alpha (sorority)|Sigma Lambda Alpha]], [[Sigma Lambda Beta]], [[Omega Delta Phi]].\n\n===Student organizations===\nOrganizations are available to students through the university that serve any interest. A complete list of campus organizations can be found on OSU's website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://campuslink.okstate.edu/organizations|title=Oklahoma State Student Organization List|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504011840/https://campuslink.okstate.edu/organizations|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=May 5, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Main|Oklahoma State Cowboys and Cowgirls}}\n[[File:Oklahoma State University Athletics logo.svg|thumb|OSU athletics logo]]\n[[File:2008 UH Cougars vs Oklahoma State Cowboys.jpg|thumb|Houston Cougars vs Oklahoma State Cowboys football game at [[:en:Boone Pickens Stadium|Boone Pickens Stadium]] in 2008]]\n'''Stats:'''\n:[[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] Division I-A\n:Conference: [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]]\n:Major Rivalries: [[Oklahoma Sooners|University of Oklahoma Sooners]]\n:Minor Rivalries: [[Texas Longhorns|University of Texas Longhorns]], [[University of Kansas Jayhawks]], [[Iowa State Cyclones wrestling|Iowa State University Cyclones]] (wrestling)\n::[[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] Championships: 52 (#4 after Stanford, USC, and UCLA)\n:: [[Oklahoma State Cowboys wrestling|Wrestling]]: 34\n:: [[Golf]]: 11\n:: [[Basketball]]: 2 (1945 and 1946)\n:: [[Baseball]]: 1 (1959)\n:: [[Cross country running|Cross Country]]: 4 (1954, 2009, 2010, 2012)\n\n::National Championships not sanctioned by NCAA: 5\n:: [[Equestrianism|Equestrian]]: 4\n:: [[College Football|Football]]: 1 (1945)\n:Athletic Director: [[Mike Holder]]\n\n===Football===\n{{Main|Oklahoma State Cowboys football}}\n10 conference titles \u2013 26 bowl games played \u2013 1988 Heisman Trophy winner and single season rushing record ([[Barry Sanders]]).\n\n===Basketball===\n{{Main|Oklahoma State Cowboys men's basketball|Oklahoma State Cowgirls basketball}}\nMen's basketball is tradition rich at Oklahoma State. Oklahoma State made the [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Championship|Final Four]] in 1995 and 2004 and was the first ever Division 1 basketball program to win back-to-back National Championships in 1945-1946.\n\n===Wrestling===\n{{Main|Oklahoma State Cowboys wrestling}}\nThe [[Oklahoma State Cowboys wrestling|Cowboy wrestling team]] brought home their 33rd [[NCAA Wrestling Team Championship|NCAA championship]] in spring 2005, scoring the most points ever by an Oklahoma State wrestling team in the NCAA. OSU won their 34th overall (and 4th consecutive) title in 2006.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.big12sports.com/sports/m-wrestl/spec-rel/031906aaa.html | title=Oklahoma State Wins Fourth Straight NCAA Wrestling Title | publisher=big12sports.com | accessdate=March 29, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061106171557/http://www.big12sports.com/sports/m-wrestl/spec-rel/031906aaa.html |archivedate = November 6, 2006}}</ref> OSU's 34 team titles are the most ever collected by a school in one sport. The Cowboys have also produced 127 individual national champions, including the sport's first-ever four-time champion, Pat Smith.\n\n===Other sports===\nSince the [[1924 Summer Olympics|1924 Olympics]], 68 [[List of Oklahoma State University Olympians|Oklahoma State University Olympians]] have won a total of 30 medals: 21 gold, four silver, and five bronze.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://okstate.com/sports/2015/3/17/GEN_2014010165.aspx|title=Olympians|website=okstate.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==Fight songs==\nNotable among a number of songs commonly played and sung at various events such as [[Graduation|commencement]], [[convocation]], and athletic games are: ''The Waving Song'', ''Ride 'Em Cowboys'' (the Oklahoma State University [[fight song]]), and the ''OSU Chant''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://okstate.com/sports/2015/3/17/GEN_201401011.aspx|title=Oklahoma State University Gameday Traditions|website=okstate.com}}</ref> At the end of every sporting event, win or lose, OSU student-athletes face the [[student section]] and sing the [[alma mater]] along with other students, faculty, alumni and staff.\n\n==People==\n{{Main|List of Oklahoma State University people}}\n\nToday, there are more than 200,000 living OSU alumni worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orangeconnection.org/s/860/index-blue.aspx?sid=860&gid=1&pgid=377 |title=OSU Alumni Association |publisher=Orangeconnection.org |accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> Prominent alumni include oil tycoon and billionaire philanthropist [[T. Boone Pickens]], actor [[James Marsden]], \"the father of the personal computer\" [[Ed Roberts (computer engineer)|Ed Roberts]], country singers [[Garth Brooks]] and [[Hoyt Axton]], former Prime Minister of South Korea [[Nam Duck-woo]], former Prime Minister of Jordan [[Adnan Badran]], US Senator [[Tom Coburn]], former [[Governor of Oklahoma]] [[Mary Fallin]],  former acting [[Surgeon General of the United States]] [[Robert A. Whitney]], Oklahoma Supreme Court Justice [[Steven W. Taylor]], [[David Noel Ram\u00edrez Padilla]] rector of [[Tecnol\u00f3gico de Monterrey]] Mexico's most prestigious university, former [[Central Bank of Somalia]] Governor [[Yussur A.F. Abrar]], production designer and drummer [[K.K. Barrett]], legal scholar [[Anita Hill]], and [[Ponnala Lakshmaiah]], an Indian politician.\n\nInterviews with OSU Alumni can be viewed and heard through the O-State Stories Project of the Oklahoma Oral History Research Program.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.library.okstate.edu/oralhistory/ostate/index.htm |title=O-State Stories Oral History Project, Oklahoma Oral History Research Program |publisher=Library.okstate.edu |date=December 8, 2010 |accessdate=February 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110409005048/http://www.library.okstate.edu/oralhistory/ostate/index.htm |archivedate=April 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty===\nA number of prominent scholars, authors and researchers have served on the OSU faculty, including poet [[Ai (poet)|Ai]], historian [[Angie Debo]], literary critic and author [[Brian Evenson]], mathematician [[William Jaco]], computer scientist and philosopher [[Subhash Kak]], chemical engineering scholar [[Nicholas A. Kotov]],  information studies pioneer and research librarian [[Edmon Low]], engineering pioneer [[J. Tinsley Oden]], and highly cited psychologist [[Robert Sternberg]] (who now teaches at [[Cornell University]]).\n\nIn recent decades, number of notable academic administrators have served on the Oklahoma State faculty, including [[Guy Bailey]] (who would serve as President of the [[University of Alabama]]), [[Ray M. Bowen]] (who served as President of [[Texas A&M]]), Hilton Briggs (who served as President of [[South Dakota State University]]), [[Robert W. MacVicar]] (who went on to become President of [[Oregon State University]]), [[James E. Martin]] (who served as President at Auburn and the [[University of Arkansas]]), [[J. Tinsley Oden]] (who served as Provost for the [[University of Texas at Austin]]), [[Robert Sternberg]] (who left to become President of the [[University of Wyoming]]), and [[Paul Torgersen]] (who served as President of [[Virginia Tech]]).\n\n===Athletics===\nCoaching alumni include OSU wrestling head coach [[John Smith (wrestler)|John Smith]], OSU football head coach [[Mike Gundy]], and former OSU basketball coaches [[Eddie Sutton]] and [[Sean Sutton]]. The Cowboys have produced several NBA players, including [[Desmond Mason]], formerly of the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]], [[Marcus Smart]] of the [[Boston Celtics]], [[Jawun Evans]] of the [[Los Angeles Clippers]], [[Tony Allen (basketball)|Tony Allen]] of the [[New Orleans Pelicans]], [[James Anderson (basketball)|James Anderson]] of the [[Sacramento Kings]], [[Joey Graham]] of the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]], [[Stephen Graham (basketball)|Stephen Graham]] of the [[New Jersey Nets]], [[JamesOn Curry]] of the [[Chicago Bulls]], [[Terrel Harris]] of the [[Miami Heat]], and former [[New York Knicks]] guard [[John Starks (basketball)|John Starks]]. [[NFL]] players [[Barry Sanders]] and [[Thurman Thomas]] also attended OSU, as did baseball All-Star pitcher [[Joe Horlen]] and All-Star third baseman [[Robin Ventura]]. Ventura went on to manage the Chicago White Sox for five seasons. Also in the [[NFL]] are former Cowboys [[Dez Bryant]] and [[Dan Bailey (American football)|Dan Bailey]] of the [[Dallas Cowboys]], and [[Kevin Williams (defensive tackle)|Kevin Williams]] of the [[Minnesota Vikings]]. Retired MMA and UFC Hall of Famers [[Randy Couture]] and [[Don Frye]], and former [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] welterweight champion [[Johny Hendricks]] wrestled at OSU. Former [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] light heavyweight champion [[Daniel Cormier]] wrestled at the university, as well as other MMA fighters including [[Mark Munoz]]. PGA professional golfers [[Rickie Fowler]], [[Scott Verplank]], [[Bo Van Pelt]], [[Charles Howell III]], [[Bob Tway]], and [[Hunter Mahan]] also attended OSU. Two-time gold medalist, ESPN analyst,  and ASA Hall of Fame inductee [[Michele Mary Smith]] played softball at OSU. [[Houston Nutt]] and [[Brent Guy]], both former players and teammates, became head coaches after serving as assistants for the Cowboy football program.\n\n==Campus buildings==\n:''Listed below are just a few of the buildings at OSU. For a complete list, visit [[List of Oklahoma State University buildings]].''\n\n===Academic buildings===\n<!-- KEEP THIS LIST IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n[[File:OSUEdmonLowLibrary2007.jpg|thumb|Edmon Low Library]]\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* 4-H Youth Development\n* Advanced Technology Research Center\n* Agriculture\n* Agriculture North\n* Animal Sciences\n* Bartlett Center for the Visual Arts\n* Biosystems and Agriculture Engineering Lab\n* Classroom Building\n* [[Colvin Center]]\n* Donald W. Reynolds School of Architecture\n* [[Edmon Low Library]]\n* Endeavor Lab\n* Engineering North\n* Engineering South\n* General Academic Building (former Spears School of Business)\